column42: The target market are the regular household users, could be a family of 4 or 5 who are in daily need of hot water, electricity, and cooling.  This is a very large segment of population.  The Ballerina system can be installed on roofs of high rise buildings very common around the world and is designed in such a way that it can provide full energy autonomy for existing and new dwellings that are far from electric public utilities.
column43: THe problem we are trying to resolve is climate change by providing the consumer a way to utilize renewable energy in a more practical way.
column51:
The Ballerina Energy System that is being developed at SES is to respond to the urgent need to lower greenhouse gas emissions from household users.    
This new product is made of a spherical sun receiver linked with a wind mill.  The Ballerina follows the sun for maximum efficiency.  It also has a dual flexible receiver that switches between a concentrated PV receiver or a hot black plate for water heating.  The windmill is located below the spherical receiver and is independent of the above system. The Ballerina base provides the brain of the system and has all the necessary controls namely: two large liquid reservoirs for hot and or/cold water storage.  A large set of batteries used to store electricity from the wind turbine and from the PV concentrated panel.  The base has also the inverter, and necessary pumps along with a general controller that would be linked to the household user showing him or her in real time how much the system is producing electricity and heat (hot/cold) and the amount of energy produced and stored.  The system can also communicate with other Ballerina"s and share energies (i.e. if one user of a house does not use all his electricity needs and has an excess), he or she can transfer this energy to another Ballerina, hence not only the optimization is on a micro-user but it could be expended to a community of users.  The name "Ballerina" was used to reflect its gracious sun tracking and simultaneous wind rotation with its flexibility to manage energy.
This product is a complete, efficient and smart renewable energy system that works during day and night.  It also combines heat storage and cold storage that could be done during the night using stored electrical energy or from wind.  The Ballerina controller decides when to produce heat/cold or when to produce electricity.  On a windy and cloudy day, the Ballerina may stop tracking the sun and position itself vertically for maximum wind energy production.  It"s built in anemometer and sun energy sensors, along with the existing energy storage system and user history would allow the Ballerina to decide how best to optimize the system for maximum energy supply.  The Ballerina is needed as it fills a need for consumers that are still undecided on what to purchase to cut down their energy needs.  Consumers are struggling whether to buy a Solar Water Heater or a stand alone PV panel system or Wind System.  Now they have the option to buy one system that optimizes all three.  The consumer does not have to worry anymore on what to buy as the Ballerina satisfies all his or her energy needs in a practical and simple way.

column27: This project aims to invent and investigate an environmentally friendly process to remove synthetic dyes and metals from textile wastewater. This is biotechnology in a very fundamental and environmentally friendly application.  It is based on using selected strains of actinomycetes that showed unique abilities in synthetic dyes degradation and heavy metals detoxification.  This method will be much less costly than the current physical and chemical treatment methods.  It will detoxify the heavy metals in the wastewater to harmless forms rather than creating a problematic solid waste that requires additional treatment before disposal. Additionally, and more environmentally important, the compounds that actinomycetes produce to break down the dyes are enzymes and proteins that themselves are easily broken down in nature to basic amino acids.

In this case selected only one objective to study and demonstrate a low-cost solution to treat textile wastewater by the action of native biodremediating bacteria in laboratory scale microcosms. Recycling of the treated effluent for agricultural purposes is another main target of this project. The project detailed objectives and role of participating teams are as follows:

1.	Development of microbial consortium to remove toxic pollutants, heavy metals and dyes from textile dye effluent in a low-cost biotreatment laboratory-scale system. (Microbiology and Chemistry teams)
2.	Enhancing the biotreatment process using suitable plants which can absorb the metals and/or enhance microbial activities (i.e. phytoremediation) (plant physiology, Microbiology and Chemistry teams).
3.	Exemplify suitable non-edible crops for irrigation by the treated effluent. (plant physiology team)
4.	Illustration of factors controlling the biotreatment process using experimental design and mathematical modeling. (Engineering, Microbiology and Chemistry teams

 our team is international and the low cost of the technique is a an advantage

column51: In recent years, a number of studies have focused on some microorganisms that are able to biodegrade synthetic compounds and biosorb heavy metals in wastewater. Our microbiology research team was able to isolate special types of naturally occurring types of filamentous bacteria - called actinomycetes - from industrial effluent at 10th Ramadan City. The abilities of these strains for degrading a variety of synthetic hydrocarbons (polycyclic hydrocarbons, pentachlorophenol, phthalates, organochlorine pesticides, triphenylmethane dyes and azo dyes) as well as abilities for bioremoval of several heavy metals (cadmium, cobalt, chromium, copper, manganese, iron, nickel, zinc and lead) have been investigated. Selected strains facilitated complete mineralization of organic compounds, thus offered a potential for finding effective bioremediation agents for purifying contaminated environments (El-Shatoury, 2001; El-Shatoury, et al., 2004). Pathway and molecular basis of organochlorines degradation as well as mechanisms of chromium removal by actinomycetes consortium has been worked out (El-Shatoury, et al., 2005; Diab, et al., 2007; Abdulla, et al., 2009; Kamal, 2009).

column51: In recent years, a number of studies have focused on some microorganisms that are able to biodegrade synthetic compounds and biosorb heavy metals in wastewater. Our microbiology research team was able to isolate special types of naturally occurring types of filamentous bacteria - called actinomycetes - from industrial effluent at 10th Ramadan City. The abilities of these strains for degrading a variety of synthetic hydrocarbons (polycyclic hydrocarbons, pentachlorophenol, phthalates, organochlorine pesticides, triphenylmethane dyes and azo dyes) as well as abilities for bioremoval of several heavy metals (cadmium, cobalt, chromium, copper, manganese, iron, nickel, zinc and lead) have been investigated. Selected strains facilitated complete mineralization of organic compounds, thus offered a potential for finding effective bioremediation agents for purifying contaminated environments (El-Shatoury, 2001; El-Shatoury, et al., 2004). Pathway and molecular basis of organochlorines degradation as well as mechanisms of chromium removal by actinomycetes consortium has been worked out (El-Shatoury, et al., 2005; Diab, et al., 2007; Abdulla, et al., 2009; Kamal, 2009).

column27: This project aims to invent and investigate an environmentally friendly process to remove synthetic dyes and metals from textile wastewater. This is biotechnology in a very fundamental and environmentally friendly application.  It is based on using selected strains of actinomycetes that showed unique abilities in synthetic dyes degradation and heavy metals detoxification.  This method will be much less costly than the current physical and chemical treatment methods.  It will detoxify the heavy metals in the wastewater to harmless forms rather than creating a problematic solid waste that requires additional treatment before disposal. Additionally, and more environmentally important, the compounds that actinomycetes produce to break down the dyes are enzymes and proteins that themselves are easily broken down in nature to basic amino acids.

yes because our objective is Adsorption is a surface phenomenon where is the dissolved substances in polluted water are attracted to and adhere to the surface of the adsorbent. The upgrading of biofilter with economic carbon material, as an adsorbent, and bioremediating bacteria can accelerate the chemical and biological detoxification of pollutants

It would serve as a cross selling marketing strategy of other apps, but most importantly to establish a user-friendly reputation in the market by being closer to the high end user.
In the second department -the Linux- the innovation would drive itself by the market contribution into the project once a version is released for public. The possibilities are endless, given that making it open-sourced means that numerous developers would want to start tweaking and implementing their own features into the system. The distribution is planned to be available for public use in no less than 12 months.

column27:
The product is innovative because to this day, no one provides turn-key finishing and furnishing in our society. Additionally, there is a specific lack of focus when it comes to low-middle income housing. With the changes that have occurred in the region, we believe a middle class will begin to surface, a class that will be aspiring to obtain modern and classic design concepts and interior finishing at affordable prices.
Additionally, the project provides a material service that is usually time consuming and exhausting, in a manner that conforms with the nature of todayâ€™s young society: fast, affordable and efficient.
column40:
The project will have several positive impacts on society, namely:
1. With any developing economy, people seek more automation and turn-key solutions to be able to devote more time to their jobs, which will become increasingly challenging. Our project allows youth the utilize their time more efficiently by effectively outsourcing the finishing and furnishing process in a reliable timely turn-key manner.

2. The project will enhance the skills and efficiency of local furniture workers, creating more jobs in the industry, and streamlining its performance to meet consumer demand.

3. By offering cheap financing, the project will allow low-middle income youth to contribute more actively to economic growth by stimulating purchases of appliances, construction materials, and other items needed for the finishing process.
column43:
The problems we are addressing are:
1. The inability of today"s young society to be able to finance their residences" finishing and furnishing. The ability to finance furniture does exist in a limited fashion, however, because finishing is usually completed by small, semi-formal companies, financing is usually not an option.

2. The lack of space-saving and efficient furniture that complies with the limited spaces available to today"s low-middle income youth. Floor space is expensive, and furniture in the region has not yet adapted to match the increasingly demanding needs of consumers.

3. The availability of skilled furniture workers that have no access to smart designs, while their skill levels can be commendable.

4. The time-consuming process that is finishing and furnishing a house or an apartment, which is faced by many low-middle income newly-weds, who are usually torn apart between their daily obligations and the errands that come with finishing and furnishing a house. Additionally, the process may be elongated by lack of funds, which is also a major issue faced by many youth, and one that can be easily solved by cheap financing.
column51: The idea behind our project is to provide turn-key finishing and furnishing for low to middle income housing. Utilizing modern concepts and space saving designs, coupled with local mass production, cheap and semi-skilled construction labor, we would be able to provide quality interior finishing at competitive prices.

column51:
[Shared-Meal] vision is to create the largest chain of restaurant alternatives around the world by encouraging cooking enthusiasts (the hosts) to operate their houses as very unique places to serve meals.

The only thing required from the hosts is to plan what they will cook for their families for a week in advance then publish their (meal plans) on [Shared-Meal] to be viewed by meal buyers (the guests). The guest selection of a meal can be based on her/his taste, availability date, the host profile, the place profile, and even shared interests! When the guest confirms a reservation, the host will only extend the planned meal to be enough for his family and for the guest. The guest share of the meal can either be sent to him through a delivery service provider to his location or it can be served in the host place where both (the host and the guest) can meet to have the planned meal and to share a mutual conversation about a topic that interests both of them.

[Shared-Meal] mission is to help cooking enthusiasts start their businesses in the meal industry using their existing resources. Also, [Shared-Meal] is expanding social networks between hosts and guests by simply connecting them to enjoy a delicious shared meal.

GoEjaza is targeting Arabic Internet users in MENA who use Internet to get information & make reservations for their trips.

-Number of Arabic Internet users who purchase online are 19,374,619.23 (1,2)
-Number of Arabic Internet users booking hotels online is 9,106,071 which represents (47%) of Arabic online consumers.(3)
-Number of Arabic Internet users booking flight tickets are 7,362,355 which represent (38%) of Arabic online consumers. These segments are leaded by both males & females in The MENA region who age from (25-44) years 
(4-5)
Sources: 
1-the number of internet users in MENA (Internet World Stats.) 
2- the percentage of internet users who shop online in MENA(Media consumption & habits of MENA Internet users (Effective Measure | Spot On PR researches.)
3-The online payment Habits (Econsultancy April 2012 )
4- (arabianbusiness.com travel survey 2008.)
5- Mastercard Survey http://www.ddarabia.com/
column29:
Main Competitors: GoEjaza have 4 types of direct & indirect competitors:

1- Arabic travel forums (example: http://travel.maktoob.com/vb - http://www.sfari.com/forums/ ) :
Pros:
The main competitors in this market, one of richest sources for Arabic travel content created by users.
Cons:
The classical method of showing the data in the forums but obstacles for user to find & obtain the information he needs from other person trip report, user needs to read too many pages with too many unnecessary replies from people who comment, for example you need to read from to 15 to 23 page as an average -for each trip report- to obtain the information you want from one person trip report he shared in the forum !.
however GoEjaza is different ?
GoEjaza platform overcomes these obstacles & make it easy for both ( user who share his trip report & user who want to benefit from this story) to easy share the information about his trip in a new effective way.

2-International review and planning sites like :
(examples: www.igougo.com - www.tripadvisor.com )
Pros:
Organized content & reviews regarding hotels or restaurants or tourism destinations
Cons:
- The content in these websites is in English.
- Majority of users of these websites are not from the region. This obviously appears in lack of Arabic users using these websites & explain large number of visitors & users of Arabic travel forums because it"s the only platform available to Arabic users to share their travel experience.
however Goejaza is different ?
First: we build goejaza.com for people who searches for original travel content by Arabic users having similar culture
Second: also we are not just a website that collect reviews about places like hotels, restaurant"s, ... etc, we go beyond that by offering a tool make you plan your trip online and made bookings for all your trip activities in one place.

3-Booking websites like (http://booking.com, http://www.fendeq.com/):
pros: 
- Provide hotels booking services
- Some websites also provide flight and cars reservations .
Some websites show users review s of hotels from tripadvisor or using simple review system in the hotel information page.
cons:
- no information about travel destination ... show only information about hotels, with minority presence of user reviews.
- No added value for users, except reservation services.
how is GoEjaza different ?
GoEjaza is a complete trip experience start from inspiring user for his next trip to crowdsource information from real traveller experience ending with planning & booking, and these competitors don"t over anything more to the user except the booking & information about hotels.

4-The Tourism Companies :
pros:
Personalized service.
Offers complete Trip packages.
Cons:
-Majority serving the customers through office during time of works. And that need to be visited thought customers.
-Don"t offers Detailed information about hotels like photos and customer reviews.
how is GoEjaza different ?
As the past competitors GoEjaa provide complete Added values services to enrich traveller trip experience. The tourism companies doesn"t provide after sale value or services to the customer.
GoEjaza Help The traveller from the inspiration, bookings of all trip activities and make acceptable from any device. Helping the user by reminding him about his daily plan portable with him from his mobile or tablet or laptop.

column27:
Customers will be people who are interested in:
a.leading a healthy lifestyle
b.dieting on their own through calorie counting scheme
c.getting credible expert advice on health, fitness and nutrition.
d.Getting customized diet and exercise plan for an additional cost
e.Following up their progress through charts and analysis

The majority of this customer base is usually women aged xx-xxx?.

Initial target market is the MENA region with initial focus in the first 2-3 years on the Arab countries starting with Egypt, UAE, Kuwait and KSA. Itâ€™s a million dollar industry. The expected annual growth will be in the range of 25-30%.
column29:
- No direct competition or similar product existing in the target market.
- Indirect competition in the form of recipe websites or forums that provide recipes and diets based on the contribution of the users, not validated information or advice from a credible source. column50:

column51:
Healthometre is a one stop nutrition and wellbeing social networking platform, the first of its type in the Middle East and Africa. Healthometre mission is to fight against obesity, nutrition related diseases and malnutrition in children and teens. It bundles expertise from nutritionists, fitness professionals and life coaches and put them into applied action plans that people can apply to live their life to the full enjoying premium health. Healthometre promotes leading a healthy life style by combining eating healthy with exercising and monitoring a health score. It can match the user with a fitness professional or nutritionists for customized training or diet plans. It is a perfect fit for the market especially the Arab countries, since five of the 10 most obese countries in the world are Arab countries. Itâ€™s a billion dollar industry globally and a million dollar industry on a regional level. Our target is to lead the regional market in 4 years time. Monetization will be through customized health plans, sponsored ads and content and paid subscriptions and also through healthometre app.

Healthometre will have a corporate social responsibility arm that conducts health awareness campaigns in poor and rural areas.

It is currently in the ideation phase.

column25:
Emad comes with the business background and the filmmaking background and handles the planning, financial planning, business strategy, and business development as well as the public relations part

Mohamed Azzouz reports to Mohamed Azzam and leads the development team in developing all the modules of the website.

column27: While registration is not restricted on any country, target market will start with middle east and then expand internationally on phases. Target audience are all individuals, whether amateurs or professionals and whether independent or commercial, interested in the filmmaking, TV, and media industry, as well as the entities such as production houses and casting agencies interested.
column30: The idea will create a clear channel to find work in this field, if you have the qualifications. It will enable the rookies to penetrate this industry faster and easier. It could also help enhance the quality of artistic production as it will help match all the resources available together so that people can find the best fit for their production.
column33:
We are tackling two major challenges in this industry, first one is casting, as it depends solely on networking and it is always a challenge to find a proper cast which sometimes result in not hiring the best people for the role, so by introducing castpace the pool of candidates would expand infinitely and the search fields and ranking will help you find the best crew and cast.
Second challenge is managing resources, so by having a unified calendar reflecting on all crew members and a unified channel of communication between resources, so castpace will be this channel and help project owners even calculate their budget and manage it using a budgeting tool.
column40: The idea is for a worldwide industry and can expand globally, and will include later on relevant sections, such as renting equipments and location, also could include, later on, relevant industries as well such as photography.
column51: Castpace.com is a complete community, portfolio database and a diversified network for all individuals and entities interested in filmmaking and media. Castpace answers a direct need in this market, as in the industry of filmmaking, networking is a key element and penetrating the existing market for newcomers is a major challenge, and there is no clear channel for networking between different resources of production. We will create this channel, creating an open market for all these individuals where they can display their work, expanding the pool of filmmakers as vast as it can get and enabling them to apply fairly in all opening projects, as well as enabling the project owners to plan and manage their resources efficiently

Second challenge is managing resources, so by having a unified calendar reflecting on all crew members and a unified channel of communication between resources, so castpace will be this channel and help project owners even calculate their budget and manage it using a budgeting tool.
column40: The idea is for a worldwide industry and can expand globally, and will include later on relevant sections, such as renting equipments and location, also could include, later on, relevant industries as well such as photography.
column51: Castpace.com is a complete community, portfolio database and a diversified network for all individuals and entities interested in filmmaking and media. Castpace answers a direct need in this market, as in the industry of filmmaking, networking is a key element and penetrating the existing market for newcomers is a major challenge, and there is no clear channel for networking between different resources of production. We will create this channel, creating an open market for all these individuals where they can display their work, expanding the pool of filmmakers as vast as it can get and enabling them to apply fairly in all opening projects, as well as enabling the project owners to plan and manage their resources efficiently

column29:
KLoad is having the advantages as the first mover offering location based transportation management services in Egypt. This gives us a strong advantage over competitors. 
Direct competition:
4-	 Trucking brokers: KLoad will have the advantage of access to the location information of a big number of trucks. In addition, shippers will have instant online access to KLoad to communicate their trucking needs.
5-	Trucking contractors: Contractors are specialized in on type of tucking service. They will have more flexibility in serving customers with using their owned trucks. Yet, they donâ€™t offer value added service offered by KLoad (such as document management/reporting). In addition, their service is not reliable because of lack of access to a wide range of truck owners. 
6-	Transportation management solutions providers (TMS). KLoad offered as SAAS (software as a service) is much lower in cost and implementation/training time than TMS. In addition, we offer location information about trucks and shipments. 
7-	Large trucking companies. Own less that 3% of trucks. Most of large trucking companies act as freight forwarders and use their fleet to serve their clients. 
Indirect competitors, Freight forwarders: Most of ports freight trucking is done via Freight forwards who offer clearance and door to door transportation to clients. KLoad short term strategy is to offer its service to class A&B freight forwarders where we can keep competitive rates and sell value added service.
column30:
Linking trucks to available load via KLoad will have a significant impact in the following areas:
1-Reduce final product cost: reducing transportation cost will reflect on final product cost. Cost reduction will make the product more competitive locally and in the international market. 
2- Reduce CO2 emission: Road transport consumes 30% of Egypt subsidized fuel and emits 28 million ton of CO2 per year. Increasing the truck productivity will reduce the amount of emitted CO2 and wasted fuel consumed by empty travelling trucks. 
4-Improve road safety: Trucks cause 40% of road accident in Egypt, a major cause of accidents is poor maintenance specially tires (Flat tires cause 20% of accidents). Increasing the economic productivity of vehicles will help owners (90% of trucks are owned by individuals) to spend on regular truck maintenance

Build company website/corporate identity (3,000 USD)
Building marketing/training material (3:000 USD)
column33:
Heavy trucks travel empty for 70-80% of return trips. The low performance of heavy trucks results in higher transportation cost due to the fuel, oil and tires wasted during the empty travel. 
15% of the trucks is Egyptâ€™s 500,000 truck are heavy trucks. The heavy trucking fleet transport 60% of the estimated 450 million ton of freight in Egypt. 
The transportation cost can be lowered by 30% if information about truck location and available loads are available. 
KLoad innovation comes from offering the following:
1- Location based service: Using Cell ID/GPS tracking to link trucks to available loads.
2- On demand TMS: Providing a low cost and easy to use Transportation Management System for small and medium enterprises. 
3- Mobile access: Providing mobile interface to drivers/truck owners to allow easy communication in addition to the desktop interface.
column43:
KLoad will charge a 10% commission and administration fees paid by truck owners.  Our target in Y13 to transport 300,000 ton with expected revenue 150,000 USD. This would be increased by 100% in Y14 and then a 30% year growth to reach revenue of 650,000 USD in 5 years.
 Other major revenue s source will be selling value added service to corporate using a freemium model. Our target in 5 years is to reach 1000 corporate subscriber with gross revenue of 1 million USD.
column50:
1-Personal experience: Karim & Hani owns a truck for 6 month. 50% of the time our truck was empty. If the truck had loads on return trips that would have reduced the price of transportation by 30%
2- Several studies have recommended the need for an information system that links trucks to available loads (USAID sponsored study in 1999 and a recent study by the Japanese International Cooperation Agency (JICA), March 2012)
*Misr National Transport Study, Jica, March 2012
*Reducing Transport Cost of Egyptâ€™s Exports, USAID, 1999
column51:
KLoad : connecting trucks to loads 
KLoad is a location based transportation management system (TMS) that connects trucks to available loads. Shipper uses an online company account to place their shipment orders. Using location based technology and available trucks details; KLoad will be able to locate trucks nearest to the shipment and directs the driver through mobile communication to the shipment.   
 KLoad will offer other value added service such as document management, shipment tracking, and history reports, and billing information to clients.

column23: Medync a project by Sync s.a.r.l.
column25:
Samer Semaan is the Co-Founder and Managing Director at Sync, an e-commerce, e-marketing and online security startup company. Holding a bachelor degree in Computer and Communication Engineering, coupled with an MBA in Marketing, Samer has over 6 years of experience in the fields of Internet and Web. With a vast and immerse knowledge within the online marketing and social media industries, Samer is a serial technology entrepreneur who recently qualified for the Maurice Fadel Prize as a top 10 finalist in 2012 re the "Tahwilat.com" project.

As a specialist as an UI and UX designer for mobile apps, Bassem Semaan has designed apps and games for iOS, Android and Windows 8. Armed with a Bachelor in graphic design and a Bachelor in Web Design, as a Co-Founder and Creative Director at Sync Bassem"s work will empower Medync to provide a simple yet powerful app. Bassem was a part of the "Tahwilat.com" project team.

A multi-disciplined designer, Maher Berro has Bachelor in Interior Design, a Minor in Graphic Design and a Master"s degree in Interactive Multimedia. With experience across the design fields, he has had -and still takes on- many roles, as a user experience designer, an interaction designer, an accessibility expert, a web designer, a front-end development, a web consultant, and a project manager. Having worked on projects across the region, as well as in Australia and the US, his exposure was on different and multi-faceted projects mostly within the higher education and telecommunication fields.

column25: Salma - Background in business: She will help with the development of the business plan and will provide support in terms of market research. She has experience coaching startups at Northeastern University through the IDEA Venture Accelerator.
column27:
Target market: college seniors and recent graduates with little or no professional experience looking for entry-level positions. Age group 20 - 26
Geographic target: We will first focus on the Gulf region and then expand our operations to the entire Middle East.
column29:
Direct competitors: Bayt.com, Monsters.com, and any job search engine in the Middle East. Given our focused differentiation strategy, we will be able to position ourselves in the market.  
Indirect competitors: recruitment agencies
column30: Our goal is to solve social issues through business. The social issue at hand is youth unemployment. Our venture will have a positive impact on the community by making it less risky for companies to hire college graduates. By reducing uncertainty, companies will find it more attractive to hire recent graduates with no professional experience. Our venture will contribute to the employment of the youth.
column32: The money will go towards web development  and the development of the psychometric test.
column33:
25% of the youth in the Arab world are unemployed. This gets more problematic given that a third of the population in the Arab World is between 15 - 29 years. Youth unemployment is very costly as it hinders the development of Arab countries. The monetary cost of youth unemployment reaches $40 to $50 billion a year. 

There is a huge gap between college students and the private sector. The private sector faces uncertainty when hiring a recent graduate as there is no background experience that they could rely on to reduce the risk associated with their selection. Moreover, college students seeking full-time positions find it very difficult to market themselves and to legitimize their skills and abilities as a great fit. 

What makes the problem more complicated is the application process. College graduates applying to entry-level positions face difficulties finding the applications online and then filling them out. Entry-level applicants usually do not have rich professional experience that supports their credentials, which leaves an undesirable amount of white space in their applications.  

Companies in the Middle East differ in terms of their speed in adopting online job applications. Many companies have an informal application process, which mainly depends on networks. This limits the pool of candidates a company has. It also confines the applicants to a small number of potential employers, which reduces their chances of getting a job offer.
column40: Our venture is very scalable. The business model works in any developing country with high youth unemployment. Our ability to scale will mainly depend on securing partnerships with companies.
column43: Applicants will be able to access the website and apply for jobs for free. However, applicants will have to pay to take advantage of other services including resume and job consultation. Private and public companies as well as multinationals will be paying annual fees for our services. SMEs will be charged on a monthly basis.
column51: Our idea is to create a website tailored for entry-level applicants. Applicants will be able to search for positions that meet their qualifications and apply online. To reduce uncertainty and the risk associated with hiring college graduates, each applicant will have to complete a psychometric test. The psychometric test assesses applicantsâ€™ business acumen, personality traits, abilities and attitudes. Each applicant will receive a score (similar to a credit score) and companies will have the freedom to decide on which range they are willing to accept. Using psychometrics reduces the risks associated with hiring recent graduates with no professional experience. It also enables companies to identify applicants that fit their companiesâ€™ culture and hence, have a better chance of succeeding at their job. column32: The money will go towards web development  and the development of the psychometric test.
column33:
25% of the youth in the Arab world are unemployed. This gets more problematic given that a third of the population in the Arab World is between 15 - 29 years. Youth unemployment is very costly as it hinders the development of Arab countries. The monetary cost of youth unemployment reaches $40 to $50 billion a year. 

There is a huge gap between college students and the private sector. The private sector faces uncertainty when hiring a recent graduate as there is no background experience that they could rely on to reduce the risk associated with their selection. Moreover, college students seeking full-time positions find it very difficult to market themselves and to legitimize their skills and abilities as a great fit. 

What makes the problem more complicated is the application process. College graduates applying to entry-level positions face difficulties finding the applications online and then filling them out. Entry-level applicants usually do not have rich professional experience that supports their credentials, which leaves an undesirable amount of white space in their applications.  

Companies in the Middle East differ in terms of their speed in adopting online job applications. Many companies have an informal application process, which mainly depends on networks. This limits the pool of candidates a company has. It also confines the applicants to a small number of potential employers, which reduces their chances of getting a job offer.
column40: Our venture is very scalable. The business model works in any developing country with high youth unemployment. Our ability to scale will mainly depend on securing partnerships with companies.
column43: Applicants will be able to access the website and apply for jobs for free. However, applicants will have to pay to take advantage of other services including resume and job consultation. Private and public companies as well as multinationals will be paying annual fees for our services. SMEs will be charged on a monthly basis.
column51: Our idea is to create a website tailored for entry-level applicants. Applicants will be able to search for positions that meet their qualifications and apply online. To reduce uncertainty and the risk associated with hiring college graduates, each applicant will have to complete a psychometric test. The psychometric test assesses applicantsâ€™ business acumen, personality traits, abilities and attitudes. Each applicant will receive a score (similar to a credit score) and companies will have the freedom to decide on which range they are willing to accept. Using psychometrics reduces the risks associated with hiring recent graduates with no professional experience. It also enables companies to identify applicants that fit their companiesâ€™ culture and hence, have a better chance of succeeding at their job. As a result, companies will reduce turnover and spend less on developmental programs.

Competition analysis
Naturally Wasla.com will have a lot of competitors as it is a website on the internet that providing same as other competitors a page for a huge database but the only differences from the other competitors is the focusing of the database and the high quality control presented in the network of the website. So here in this section, there is a spot on Wasla.com competitors and what differentiate Wasla.com service from others.
Primary-Direct competitors:
Main competitors are normal search engines (E.g Google, Yahoo, Bing, Msn).
As for Google or other search engines they lack reliability and list the results according to the number of viewers that provide weak image about the business quality, and it list a lot of irrelevant results as well as wasting a lot of time and effort to get specific company through search a massive database with billions of inputs .Beside that if the user is specific with the search keywords still he will have to go through huge results list. Therefore, it didnâ€™t provide reliable results which will decrease the accuracy or the results.
Indirect Competitors:
Websites offering similar services as (Alibaba and Tamkeen) representing the main secondary competitors for Wasla.com. Alibaba and Tamkeen are website that are competing Wasla.com globally.
For Tamkeen is a website that is totally different from Wasla.com network. It is only same as Wasla.com in the point of dealing with the SME"s in Egypt. But Tamkeen have a different way than Wasla.com as dealing with the SME"s in Egypt in a developmental way and also working with them in a detailed staff or help the SME"s from their scratch to their launch.
For Alibaba is a website that includes transactions of buying, selling, and outsourcing. They are contradicting to Wasla.com focus which is a network of integrated, huge database for the benefit of SME"s in Egypt. Ali Baba is a family of Internet-based businesses, which operates the leading global e-commerce platform for small businesses around the world. In June 30, 2012, the platform had 29.4 million registered users from more than 240 countries and regions and showcased 2.5 million supplier storefronts.
Alibaba although it provides kind of similar service, still it lacks a lot of what differentiate Wasla.com service than any other website. As its ranking based on seniority on the website and it donâ€™t guarantee the high quality of companies that recognize our services than any other competitors and furthermore it donâ€™t allow members to review other companies or give their feedback about the transactions it did through the website which hinder their communication with their customers. In addition to that, wasla.com offers much special services for its customers that guarantee the delivering of a unique value for our customers and ensure their loyalty.
Other competitors:
Other competitors could be normal brokers but those brokers have limited network and canâ€™t cover all fields. Plus, they have inaccurate data about the companyâ€™s quality and performance. Furthermore, brokers could have unethical decisions that are avoided by our website.
Competitive position:
No other business in Egypt focuses exclusively on the quality of the information that can be needed by the SME"s in their business field or integrating them in a one website on the internet. This benefit or this competitive advantage can provide the website a high attention getter to it from different levels of companies or sectors in the Egyptian market.
The search engines as Google, Yahoo, and msn that are competing all around the world. But for Wasla.com website after the first 5 years of operation in the market, it will be presented in Cairo but with an easier way to the SME"S around Egypt .Due to that Wasla.com will reach to their specific information in its integrated network for different databases. In addition to that,Wasla.com website will offer a high quality database that integrate different information that are in a need by the SME"S .Then Wasla.com will be expanded in another three countries after the 5 years of operations.
For Wasla.com the different search engines and the other websites in the market for the same purpose of giving the internet users a huge database for different information are shaping a huge competition for Wsal.com in the market .And these competitors also are profitable in the market and successful. But Wasla.com has an integrated network with a competitive advantage over the other competitors, which as it was mentioned the integration and the focusing in different business sectors that will be needed by the SME"s in their business. All these information will be in a one place with a high quality control.

column33:
As AUC witnesses a huge change to the food outlets seen in its new campus, which comes in a 
time when the newly-enrolled students reached 1,200 students this year, ordering food became a 
major issue at AUCâ€™s new campus. Instead of using breaks for extracurricular activities and/or taking a break, as they are was meant to be used, students and faculty find themselves in a race against time to get the food they want and have the time to eat it while doing any other commitments. What seems to be a solution is to avoid ordering food during assembly hours (a break given to the whole AUC community, it is from 1-2 pm everyday) and utilizing the 15-minute breaks between classes, but this never works, because everyone does it. The main reason for this problem is that AUCâ€™s food outlets system was not built to accept such a huge inflow, especially during assembly hours and upon bus arrivals. Not only does this annoy the AUC community, it affects the profits these outlets make as well; we believe that the solution to this is for AUC to have an efficient pre-ordering system. Engezny originated to solve this problem.
column51:
Engezny is a food pre-ordering system that allows both customers to order food from any food outlet without being there physically and to pick it up at 
the time they wish. The pre-ordering system allows its users to log in through a website and to order food and also pay for it.
The purpose of the  Engezny  is to save  the  time and effort wasted on waiting to order in the different outlets due to the long waiting lines. In addition, Engezny aspires to enhance the quality of food ordered through having the outlets aware of the orders beforehand and providing them  with enough time and space to schedule preparing the orders rather than rushing them out due to crowded outlets.

As we are student at the American University in Cairo AUC, we attempt to first implement the project on small scope on campus because we already face a problem in food queues in breaks.

column50:
â€¢	Global solar market was $91.6 billion in 2011, up from $71.2 billion in 2010 ( Clean Edge RF) 
 
The PV installed globaly is about 27.4  GW according to annual PV market report, 2012 MarketbuzzÂ® issued by NPD Solarbuzz. The installation in 2012 is expected is be around 30 GW with 13 GW for the first half of the year.
CPV installation for 2012 is close to .1 GW and to grow to 1.2 GW in 2016.
Two key factors made CPV tech. come short to PV in installation are:

1.	Price
2.	Ground mounting necessary for most of the CPV systems while fig (3) and fig (4) shows that the majority of PV installations are not ground mounted 

â€¢	And our system manage to solve this two problems to expand with a CPV system into the PV market.
column51:
We provide cheap solar technology with high conversion efficiency (about 30%, better than 97% tech. in the market).


We designed a new (non-tracking ) Concentrated PV (CPV)system. Our concentrator has the ability to concentrate sun from any angle, removing the need for expensive, heavy and huge tracker and mounting structure used by current CPV systems which use ordinary convex lens or mirrors. It Brings cheap light weight CPV system to the market that can be installed on roofs unlike current CPV technologies.

column51: The idea of The College Experience comes at a time when higher institutions of education are expanding and blooming in the Middle East. The aim is to increase pride of affiliation with a university or college and to make this association into an idea that promotes the role of post-secondary education in this part of the world. We believe this can be achieved through the building of a healthy competition between universities and when this competition is achieved, the role of The College Experience will be to display this educational heritage to the public. At the same time, we believe that running a business which is caused-based and gives back to society as it grows is a business that will be able to sustain itself in the future. This is achieved with our multiple affiliations with charities that help reduce poverty in Pakistan and charities that promote health issues in the Middle East.

column5: Pediatricion at Abu Rish Hospital in Cairo
column25: Ahmed connects with families who have relatives or friends living in Cairo"s worst region " Madinat El Zabalyeen". Our enterprise"s initiative is to tap into the hearts and creativity of young people in that region and have them help us in terms of recycling old newspers, magazines, candy wrappers etc.. into fashionable bags. Marwa is in charge of branding and distribution, whereas Soraya is a social media guru, using all social mediums to help promote our concept and target across. I am the co-founder and powerhouse of the operation, as I have lived in Cairo for many years and feel disappointed in how garbage continues to grow in this lovely city and one might can say " why not benefit from it and help society"s poor, if there"s too much of it".

Smart Control System introduces services to users as the following:
first: Reduces the Consumption of Electrical energy in a building as it senses if there is no people in the place, it will shut down all devices automatically in this place and turns them on again when it senses people in the place.

column5: Manager Designer ( VFX, 3D, Montage et Graphisme)

column27:
The first region that will be concerned by my project is MENA then europe, Asia and America at the end.
My main customers will be Students and  Teachers  then other peoples
column29:
My direct competitors are "soft copy books".
My indirect competitors are coffeshops, playing centers, Electronic games : These are not encouraging people to read books
column30:
My project will encourage people to read books. They will get hard copy of their preferable book that they select in our data base.
Poor people and student will not be obliget to pay a big amount to get a book because they will hire it for a limited period with a small amount.
column32: Once i get 50 000 $, I will hire an office, recrute staff and i will hire a big store where to collect all books.
column33:
My Idea will try to solve the problem of the high cost of books. The reader will not be obliged to buy every book that he read and then keep it in his cupboard without any use.
The reader will not be obliged to take transportation and go to public libraries because he will get the book at his house only.
Usually public libraries are having a limit number of books wich is  renewed after a long time (one year almost). But in My shared library there will be a new books avery day coming from the participation of new readers.
column40:
Every day new people will participate in my Library and they will send a book for avery one to get inscription in my Library. With this way my data base of books will increase daily and the number of participants also because a big diversity of books will be there.
In the hole world people are interested by reading books so my project can be spread all over the world
column43:
For Exemple 1 000 000 person will give a book to participate in my Library. Like this i will have 1000 000 book. If monthly 30 % of books are hired so 300 000 book will be exchanged.
For every book exchanged, the reader will pay 2.5 $ Dollar. 2 dollars will be the cost of sending and receiving back the book . 0.5 dollar will be my profit in every exchange.
It means my profit will be monthly : P = 300 000 x  0.5 $ = 150 000 $ Monthly
column50:
I have proposed my idea to many  students and teachers. All of them are interessted in participating and getting there book as hiring  through my SharedLibrary.
I have checked the cost of sending books by post, it is a small amount comparing with the cost of the book itself.
column51: My Idea is to make a global library that any person can participate in it by giving a book. All books received from participants will be saved in a website so any one can enter and select a book. The reader can get the selected book at his house by paying a small amount wich will includ the post transfer fees.

column5: Project manager in a Multinational car maker and business owner
Program manager for broadband, portals and multimedia in orange lab , Cairo
column25:
Tamer Ahmed
CEO and co-founder
17+ years of experience in the IT and telecom field
Founder of OGRA and a couple of other startups in the field of technology
Previous experience in multinational telecommunication corporates
10 years of Experience in the VAS (value added services) and mobile applications
column27:
Service customers target is the manufactures and
authentic medicine importers. Mainly pharmaceutical, spare parts
and food manufactures. They are our customers. Our
users are the people who use their mobile to send the
authentication SMS mainly they are class A and class B
customers.
column29:
Competition in this market come from the water marks and sealed packaging technology providers . The
advantages of Assly are
1. Easy to use (Just SMS which is available on every mobile
handset)
2. Cost effective as printing the scratch cost will cost
no more than 0.01 US$ per package
3. Very secure as it uses high level security codes
with the same technology currently used for mobile
scratch card proofed to be spoof-free and highly
reliable.
column30:
MENA region had no such service but it all shares the
same thing "A lot of falsified goods" Medicine, food,
cars spare parts. you name it !! customers are always
suspicious about the goods they buy. One good
example is the electrical accessories market in Egypt
where brands like Siemens and GE suffer from cheap
grey market products which may cause fire in customer
place. Saudia Arabia , UAE, Tunisia, Algeria, Morocco
and Jordan are all suffering the same issues.
Wherever there are falsified goods in the market
"Assly" can make a real difference by offering secure and reliable service that can protect against falsification. 
For the businesses like pharmaceuticals and spare parts manufactures and distributors such service will mean less profit losses and more fund to spend on research and development.
column33:
The falsification of goods; specially medicine and car spare parts is a huge problem in MENA region. Estimates of counterfeited medicine in Egypt only is estimated at 3 Billion EGP per year (source http://www.elshaab.org/thread.php?ID=39962)
Jordan is another country that suffers the same problem with 10 Billion Dinar (Source http://www.alfanonline.com/show_news.aspx?nid=18814&pg=4)
All around the world the market of falsified goods including medicine is estimated between 70 to 120 Billion US$ !!
In Africa there are 700,000 death per year due to falsified medicine.
The number of people who die due to falsified car spare parts is huge as well.
Watching this video can show how severe is this in our region.

http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wijRo6riWEw

column43:
Service will be sold to the manufactures on a pay-as-
you-go model so they pay for each code that they print
on their packages. Primary price is estimated at 0.25
EGP per code. Developing a CRM system for the
manufactures based on the fact that the service
database contains their customer contacts already can
be another source of revenue.
If the loses are 1.2 B EGP yearly and Assly system can
return 10% of that(120M) at the cost of 10M only then
it will make a lot of sense for the manufactures !

Primary price is estimated at 0.25 EGP per code.
Another source of revenue can be offering the service
as a premium SMS for the end users.
Expected revenue are to sell 1 million code by first year
(250K EGP) and by third year of operation 5 million
codes (1 million EGP). Expanding to other countries will
triple those numbers.
column50:
Assly had proofed the concept on many trials with
potential customers like Bridgestone agent in Egypt.
The prototype for the service had been proofed to work
with remarkable performance and simple customer
experience.
column51:
Asly is a start-up company that had already started
to market the service of checking genuine goods. The
company plans to be the first and most trusted
company offering this service in MENA region. The
brand "Genuine" or "Asly"  should always become the first word that come to customers mind when they want to check how
genuine is any product. Through the use of easy to
remember short code "9104"; it will be published
through all media and found in front of customers in
pharmacies and doctors" clinics.

The number of people who die due to falsified car spare parts is huge as well.
Watching this video can show how severe is this in our region.

http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wijRo6riWEw
column40:
MENA region had no such service but it all shares the
same thing "A lot of falsified goods" Medicine, food,
cars spare parts. you name it !! customers are always
suspicious about the goods they buy. One good
example is the electrical accessories market in Egypt
where brands like Siemens and GE suffer from cheap
grey market products which may cause fire in customer
place. Saudia Arabia , UAE, Tunisia, Algeria, Morocco
and Jordan are all suffering the same issues.
Wherever there are falsified goods in the market
"Assly" can make a real difference
column43:
Service will be sold to the manufactures on a pay-as-
you-go model so they pay for each code that they print
on their packages. Primary price is estimated at 0.25
EGP per code. Developing a CRM system for the
manufactures based on the fact that the service
database contains their customer contacts already can
be another source of revenue.
If the loses are 1.2 B EGP yearly and Assly system can
return 10% of that(120M) at the cost of 10M only then
it will make a lot of sense for the manufactures !

Primary price is estimated at 0.25 EGP per code.
Another source of revenue can be offering the service
as a premium SMS for the end users.
Expected revenue are to sell 1 million code by first year
(250K EGP) and by third year of operation 5 million
codes (1 million EGP). Expanding to other countries will
triple those numbers.
column50:
Assly had proofed the concept on many trials with
potential customers like Bridgestone agent in Egypt.
The prototype for the service had been proofed to work
with remarkable performance and simple customer
experience.
column51:
Asly is a start-up company that had already started
to market the service of checking genuine goods. The
company plans to be the first and most trusted
company offering this service in MENA region. The
brand "Genuine" or "Asly"  should always become the first word that come to customers mind when they want to check how
genuine is any product. Through the use of easy to
remember short code "9104"; it will be published
through all media and found in front of customers in
pharmacies and doctors" clinics.

column51: ENCODE studio is a "design by research studio" created by the collaboration of young architects that have come together to break the status quo and go beyond the typical architecture studio by developing the pragmatic use of various digital media in the architecture and the design practice. They are dedicated to explore integrated architecture computational design techniques and innovative design systems on different scales from object to field aiming for a more significant Egyptian presence in the global design market.  ENCODE team believes in research as a catalyst of innovation in the design industry. They intended to be a conduit between design professionals, the educational and the manufacturing sectors by investigating various digital and physical computational tools based on the mathematical and material logic of natural systems, exploring the potentials of digital design and fabrication techniques to correlate education, profession and design industry.

column51:
Every body knows We had a huge unemployment problem in Egypt and Mena  area We have an unemployment rate around 12% in Egypt. Even most of the employed young people needs second income source to be able to support their families. 
On the other hand many people are very busy and stressed and they will be very happy if we can find them someone who can finish the simple daily tasks that takes much time and  effort for a reasonable price and  this is why we are building taskty.

Taskty is a simple tasks  assigning platform. Our job will be to connecting those people together ,ensure quality of service, offer a convenient payment method  and make sure that the process is safe.
 
So how does it work?
When need to hire someone for a task you can submit your task with all the details and the required talents that should present in the service provider to finish the job and the price you offer. 
 Freelancers will start to apply for the task until  you choose one of them. we will help you to choose better by our advanced recommendation and rating system. 
once the task is done and you are satisfied we will finalize the task, transferring the money and record the ratings. 
we just published an extensive customer survey to get a list with the services with the highest need but here are some examples: 
If you have a small business we will help you to hire freelancers to finish graphic design (logo flyer , b card etc),copywriting job , simple legal advising or event organization .  
Also you can ask for someone to deliver you something, help you with cooking, photographing an event or even do house cleaning or a simple maintenance.

With 63% of entrepreneurs belief of entrepreneurial potential, but business discontinuation or failure to start due to lack of entrepreneurial knowledge, access to networks and finance; empowerment to develop and sustain their businesses in a community of 27.1% unemployment rate, millions of immigrants seeking job opportunities, brain drainage, splitting families apart and economy decline. PIN IT will provide this target market with their needs, answer their questions, get them altogether enabling them to access network of partner universities, academic and media sponsors and be mentored by key figures in different fields to reflect on their business, access finance and leap to next steps impact communities generating wealth and job opportunities for others being charged 800$ less than a team member half income. This market has huge potential of expansion after growing in Cairo the center of entrepreneurial activity to other needy location, generating jobs, empowering youth to access finance and create new markets, it is a sustainable job and market generator, creating 75 jobs minimum per graduating company.

column19: Graphic Designer, Social Media Advisor, Project Management, Marketing
column25:
Mariam Hamidaddin, Creative Director of offline activities
Graphic Designer with a background in cultural management, Mariam has the knowledge to organize art and cultural events and campaigns from A to Z. She organizes "Open Mic" events in Jeddah which take place monthly.

Mozn Hamidaddin,  Communications Director
Graphic Designer with a background in marketing strategy and analysis. Mozn is strong in identifying strengths and weaknesses, finding areas for improvement or considering consequences of not implementing new strategies. Furthermore, comparison of competitors" current and future strategies.

Soraya Darwish, Managing Director and acting Social Media Director
Graphic Designer, blogger, and artist with a background in marketing, social media, e-commerce, and project management, Soraya"s research in the art and design field has introduced her to the problems that the creative scene in Saudi Arabia is facing and how they can be solved.
Furthermore, she has formed a wide network of creative professionals , gallery owners, and a community of artists and art enthusiasts which are all necessary for the success of the venture.

Yousef Alshaikh, Creative Director of online activities


Mariam, Mozn, and Soraya all successfully completed KAUST"s VentureLab program in Fall 2012.
column27:
Our target market is Saudi Arabia"s main cities: Jeddah, Riyadh, and Dammam.

Our target customers are 18 to 35 year old visual creatives, mostly visual artists, graphic designers, and photographers.
column29:
Direct Competitors:
Tasami
Visual Arts Club
Darat Safiyah Bin Zagr
Naqsh

Indirect Competitiors:
Tashkeil
THE LOFT
column30:
- Creating a community for creatives that encourages collaboration, exchanging ideas, developing one"s skills and learning new ones

- Empowering and incubating creatives to increase the number of creative agencies in Saudi Arabia, thus boosting the economy and creating new job opportunities in the industry

- Supporting start ups and initiatives by connecting them to creatives, thus accelerating the process of starting a new venture, initiative, or even launching a social campaign
column32:
$22,000 : Design and development of Onqoud website in order to expand our network and database and lead to securing enough sponsorship and funds to rent the space for our headquarters.

$12,000: Marketing and branding budget for 1 year, including 1 PR event in each city (Jeddah, Riyadh, Dammam)

$16,000: administrative expensive and running costs (management team salaries, renting venues for workshops, physical assets such as art supplies,
column33:
Over 90% of creatives in Saudi Arabia believe there is a lack of:
- collaborative workspace where they can work together and learn from each other
- creative communities and networking opportunities where they can find support from like minded people and receive feedback on their work
- affordable workshops where they can develop their skills
- online database that gives creatives in Saudi Arabia more exposure and provides the opportunity to connect with creatives with the same specialty

Furthermore, start ups and social initiatives need the support of creatives and therefore Onqoud"s platform will facilitate the process of finding creatives.

Onqoud aims to collaborate with likeminded ventures and initiatives in order to amplify the positive impact on the community and to enrich the creative scene in Saudi Arabia.
column40:
- Renting kiosks to small businesses to sell their products
- Opening branches in Jeddah first, then Riyadh and Dammam
- Strategic partnerships with existing similar ventures and universities with art and design majors
- Signing with job listing websites, with a focus on creative job listing websites (i.e: Onqoud members have to create accounts on the website we sign with)
- mobile app allowing users to access the profiles of creatives, video tutorials, and job posts on their mobile devices
column43:
- Workshops
- Advertising on video tutorials, social media channels, and e-newsletter
- Membership packages for the collaborative workspace, for individuals and start ups
- Rentable meeting and workshop rooms and event area
- Commissions for referring clients to creative companies and agencies
- Renting kiosks to
column51:
Onqoud is an incubator and hub for creatives in Saudi Arabia, providing an online and offline platform for the creative community to learn, create, and share.

OFFLINE: workshops, events, exhibitions, collaborative workspace
ONLINE: video tutorials (Arabic and English) , sharing portfolio via profile on the website, job posts

Our mission is to create an art and design movement in Saudi Arabia that encourages collaboration and to lead it by empowering creatives and helping them develop their skills and reach their full potential.

Our vision is to establish a community of creatives that will make Saudi Arabia"s creative scene one of the richest in the region.

column25: I am be the leader of the project, I will be forming the team that will build and supervise the software.
column27: First Saudi Arabia, then the Gulf States. After the softwareâ€™s success, I would start expanding in the MENA. Afterwards I would go globally. The main customers are governmental traffic departments and corporations that offer traffic control solutions.
column29: The main competitors are companies that offer traffic control solutions. On the other hand, the indirect competitors are legislator who might enforce harsh traffic laws in order to reduce traffic accidents. However, the legislatorâ€™s solutions constantly proved to be ineffective my main targeted market (Saudi Arabia).
column30: The business would have a huge positive effect on the community. The reason behind this is that the main target of the business is to achieve a positive externality on the community (reduce traffic accidents) which would have a huge positive impact. Reducing traffic accidents would save lives by reducing related fatalities. It would also reduce injuries, which would also reduce medical costs and insurance.  Moreover, it would reduce the $6 billion that Saudi spends each year on traffic accidents management. Another positive economic effect would be that traffic jams would be reducing, because of the reduction I the number of accidents that caused it. Reducing traffic accidents might also help the environment, because of the reduction in number of vehicles being disposed each year. The business would also create high tech well-paid jobs for employees who will work on developing and operating the software. Saving lives, having positive effects on the economy and the environment makes TARS a win-win business for both the investors and the community.
column32: To develop and produce the software.
column33: The main problem is traffic accidents. Saudi Arabia has a very high rate of traffic accidents. Moreover, most of the solutions implemented to solve this problem proved to be ineffective. According to Saudiâ€™s Secretary-general of Intelligent Transport Systems (ITC), in 2012 the Saudi government spent $6 billion on the management of traffic accidents, while traffic accidents fatalities increased 10% (Source: Jiffry, F., 2012. Experts rate Saudi roads as among the worldâ€™s most dangerous. Arab News, [online] 8 November. Available at: < http://www.arabnews.com/saudi-arabia/experts-rate-saudi-roads-among-world%E2%80%99s-most-dangerous> [Accessed 26 January 2013].)
column40: There is a regional demand for cheap innovative solutions for traffic accidents. The business is very scalable because it can satisfy this demand with little changes made to the software. Moreover, these changes and tweaks to the software that will make it suitable for other markets are few (mainly maps and interface language). The few changes indicate that there will be an increase in profits without a proportionate increase in costs.
column43: selling the software, subscriptions to the software, and the after sales services.
column50: The first step was to investigate traffic accidents reduction solutions implemented in Saudi Arabia and the Gulf states. The solutions were assessed by comparing the number of traffic accidents, related number of fatalities/injuries in different years. All these numbers had an increasing trend, while the solutions implemented failed constantly. Moreover, most of the solutions were legislations and laws which produced general unconcentrated efforts to deal with the problem.
column51: TARS collects traffic accidents data, analyse it, and help implementing and evaluating its solutions. TARS will have a smart phone app that traffic officers use to report traffic accidents that they handle (Reporting locations, times, number of injuries, and deaths). The smart phone app will crowd source the data collection process creating a huge mine of data for the software to analyse. The software will produce an interactive map with each cluster of accidents represented as a point. The colour of the each point represents the frequency of accidents (red for high, orange for medium, and yellow for low). When clicking on any accidents point a profile will appear, containing the pointâ€™s details. The details include its number, status, and historical data. The employees must suggest a solution to reduce the accidents in this point, using data that the software analysed. After inserting the solution, the software starts tracking the change in the rate of accidents, deaths, and injuries in the point. Solutions can be viewed and sorted depending on district, status, and rate of change. This feature enables the traffic department to identify the employees or teams with best/worst solutions, which can become a field of competition. The software will be able to learn from the users and starts recognising patters, which enables it to start suggesting solutions for accident points, or even modifications for current implemented solutions.

column51:
Quantum solution is the first company in Egypt trying to cover an engineering market gap by providing full advantageous selling packages that include wide range of presentation tools services and products such as 3D physical models, graphic design services, and 3D animation video walk-through, in addition to other selling products and packges.
The firm is initially opening at Cairo, whereas it is offering a complete package at high quality with effective cost which aims to provide excellent support services to the leading companies, big group corporate and engineering offices.
Quantum Solution is using development of design, visualization, presentation and other instruments that are vital for successful project marketing, whereas we are aimed to satisfy existing demand and to fill the market gap. Our company is able to provide full range of professional services, meeting client"s individual needs in one place at less time and lower cost. 
Quantum Solution poses a considerable development potential and is destined for success due to strong competitive advantages. QS is a specialized company capable of building 3D physical models of architectural projects with different options and varsities, so the client does not have to order it from China (most common solution) sacrificing the quality of the project and/or burning extra costs. Quantum Solution so far is the only company operating in the local market that provides full range of promotional tools for engineering and architectural companies. The company possesses pricing advantage compared to overseas competitors due to lower labor costs and discounts provided for full package services. Moreover the company possesses strong industry expertise as well as good knowledge of local market, which altogether ensures outstanding quality of the final product.
Quantum Solution is a bright and promising cash-generating startup with high level of investment attractiveness and significant development potential.

column51:
Our "Science communication" through low cost material communicating resourcefulness and productivity aspiration.

*We are doing that through merging 5 things together:
-Physics
-Practical skills
-Technical knowledge
-Interpersonal skills
-Moral lessons

"The 1st letter of every term are the project name (PPTIM)"

*PPTIM consists of 3 arms:
-B2D
-MILE 
-Robot-Khana

*We are trying to apply this concept through 3 different arms, it is the same idea and concept, but the tool is a little bit different in every project.

>>>1st Arm: (B2D "Born To Discover"), Target age: 8-12

Aim: Help the kids to be more creative, also to take them out of the digital world and put them in the real and practical one; because the life is not ideal as we see in the PCs. All that through an edutainment way, when merging physics, practical skills, technical knowledge, interpersonal skills and moral lessons in an interesting program.


Cause: We believe that investing in the kids is more important than investing in the adults. They are the future builders. Also, their mind are like a white paper, then, if you succeeded in filling this paper with the write words. You will be able to hope for a better world for them.

Description: It"s a program for the age 8-12 Years. Through this program we give them all the skills mentioned before through building robots. This program is divided into a series of workshops. The kids are divided into teams then they begin their work with the help of the instructors. The instructors give them the knowledge and the skills in a practical way through building their own robots using the CORDian kits.

Tools:
-Kits provided by CORD, it contains materials that we can find around us and we always see daily like: rulers, rubbers, syringes, hoses and much more. The idea is how to merge and connect these materials and make functional robots. These kits are categorized into families and every family into levels. These kits help the instructors through the program. The R&D department in CORD is the responsible department for developing these kits.
-Also the well-trained instructors are the human resource.


>>>2nd Arm: (MILE "Making Inventors Life Easier"), Target age: 12-16

Aim: As it is shown in the name of the project, making inventors life easier.

Cause: Widening the range of using the CORDian kits to make the largest segment take benefit from the idea.

Description: We consider the kits itself as a separate project; these kits can be sold in the stores, they can be independent with the help of the included manual, which contains the steps you should do to build the robot using the kit. It doesn"t need a course or a program in this case and for that age.

Tools: Only the CORDian Kits.

>>>3rd Arm: (Robot-Khana), Target age: 16-24
"Khana is the pronunciation of a Turkish word means Place"

Aim: Helping the youth to better understand the physics and the technical knowledge they have learned in a practical way. Also developing their creativity, technical skills and interpersonal skills as well. All that to make them be able to take the better decision, be more productive in their lives and change their societies to better ones.

Cause: We also believe in investing in the youth; because they are the builders of the present or the near future.

Description: It"s Robots Competitions that held in different places like colleges, high schools, clubs or any other youth community. The participants take their knowledge from open sessions provided by CORD then they participate to make the competition"s mission. It"s a non-profitable project, as it is also a volunteering activity. It"s like a student to student activity in different communities managed by CORD, we provide an organizational manual that helps the passionate students to start their CORDian branch in their college or school. Step by step from establishing the branch till making the competition through the different phases like: teams registration, competition"s design, book of rules design, open sessions, robots testing, .. etc.

Objective: To make sustainable CORDian branches -Which are volunteering activities, non-profitable and from students to students- in different youth communities all over Egypt, then all over Africa and The Arab World.

Tools:
-The organizational manual provided by CORD which contains all the info. needed by the organizers
-The open sessions provided by CORDian instructors which contains the technical material needed by the participants
-The CORDian kits provided by CORD
-The sponsors that give the fund support to these student activities



*Note: The common thing between the three projects is "the CORDian Kits", which is our main tool, it is also in continuous development.
