column5: MBA Candidate at IE Business School. Madrid, Spain.
column25:
Karim: Product and business Development and operations
Karim will manage relationship with the academic institutions as well as reaching and selecting candidate students. He will also manage the online platform and user experience. Karim, has is a business analytics consultnat with experience with both technology and extracting value from data.
Tarek:
Tarek will manage relationships with partner banks and all creditors. He will also overview the finance of the company in terms of budgeting, risk management and planning. To do that, Tarek will capitilize on his experience and contacts in the banking sector.
column27:
Borrowers (in Phase 1) will be young men and women between the age of 20 and 35 who would like to pursue a higher education degree both locally and internationally. We estimate those to be around 60,000 (source CAPMAS website). We also estimate the average degree cost to be 10,000 EGP. Assuming an average student would need around 40% of the cost to be financed through a loan then we have a potential loan market of 200,000,000 EGP. Naturally, we would like to start with the high end segmentâ€”degrees from reputable universities both locally and abroad. This strategy should help us to smooth our startup phase with minimal administrative cost, gain quick wins, and establish brand credibility and operational expertise. In later years we would like to cover less costly programs that are needed in the Egyptian job market and even all types of informal education. 
Benefits for borrowers:
-	Banks in Egypt only lend to employees using their salaries as collateral. This makes education loans almost absent in the local market. 
-	Even loans secured from other sources are not tailored for education, i.e. do not include a grace period which the student will not have an income. 
-	Higher chances of employment after graduation
2)	Lenders side:
i.	Partner Bank
o	Chance to experiment with this new product in the Egyptian market
o	Conversational capital in terms of social value created by this business
o	They need us because we will provide relationships with the academic institutes which is critical for this type of product
o	We will also enhance the chances of repayment through matching selected students with career opportunities.
o	Interest earned through a relatively safe loans
o	Potential future clients
ii.	NGOs
o	Opportunity to help more students with less funds
o	Investment in Egyptâ€™s human capital
o	More control over the process
iii.	Regular individuals
Those are regular individuals interested in this type investment
o	A fixed income alternative that pays higher than bank deposits
o	Interest in supporting particular candidates (family, alma mater, co-workers)
iv.	Private Sector
o	Corporate social responsibility
o	Enhanced talent supply
column30: Elevation of education level by enabling talented students to obtain higher decrees that will increase their productivity and income.
column33: Many talanted Egyptians cannot get access to higher education because of lack of finance. In fact, uncollateralized educa
column40: We are planning to start with top schools locally and abroad. This will help us gain operational expertise and credibility. Beyond that we would like to target more programs based on the requirement of the local economy. After becoming national leaders in education loans we can either expand geographically to other Arab countries or transfer our skills to SMEs and microfinance.
column51: The idea is to create a crowd finance platform for talented individuals who seek to obtain higher education using their education degree and anticipated post-graduation earnings as collateral. We create agreement with specific higher education institutes to facilitate the loan transfer directly to them as well as to guarantee repayment by the students, e.g. withholding the degree and other services in case of no payment. We will also play an active role with connecting such students with future employers who would like to enhance their talent supply in a specific discipline. The lenders could be a partner bank, NGOs/social funds, companies and individuals interested in this type of fixed income.

column5: Retail Quality assurance advisor at Vodafone Egypt
column25:
Hosam Mesallum  
It is the role of the CEO to manage the whole organization and to set goals to pursue and future strategies to apply, and also allocating the resources according to the business needs.

Anas Fayed
Responsible for 3 main divisions.
1- Production : Responsible for making product designs for the technical point of view, and converting it into real products.
2- Quality Management : Applying Quality Standards while conducting the manufacturing process whether we are in-sourcing or outsourcing the production.
3- Supply Chain Management : Adapting the tone or the pace of the production to suit the market needs.  

Ahmed Ali
Responsible for the business development and acquiring data from the market, and acting accordingly to its needs in terms of modifications on our products or making entirely new products.
Also he is responsible for the marketing department; Starting with creating new products or solutions, and communicating our selling prepositions to the target segments, and assuring smooth delivery of the products to attain the best possible customer satisfaction.
column33:
In the B2B section comes all the creativity you might imagine, totally what we might produce is dependent on what the client asks for, and we are asked to develop solutions for the problems that the companies might face, so we need very creative thinking, but cost efficient as well in order to be able to compete at the scale of a main B2B provider.
We may categorize the various types of accessories as in the following " plastic made, sewed or assembled products, metal products" and also categorizations by usage.
And then we develop a skill matrix to describe to what extent are we skillful making this product.
The problem is that it needs very strong operations, so we outsource usually, but our skill level increases by time, and from one deal to another.

This video is one year ago, we made more progress in the B2B direction for making more deals with Vodafone Egypt.

column27:
We are starting within Egypt (planning to expand within Africa and the Middle-east later on). Our target customers are divided into the following:
1-Enterprises that have existing/ potentially need energy saving plans.
2-Middle class that can afford initial higher cost for products, with guaranteed savings in the future.
column32:
1- We would like to invest of course in our awareness campaigns with marketing force.
2- Starting small start-ups based in the villages to be based on renewable energy sources (such as roof-top plantation and solar panels).
3- Sponsoring potential student"s research projects and activities.
column43:
Our funding plan is based on multiple axes:
1-Renewable products: products made out of re-used/recycled materials to be made with a low budget. This will be part of both funding and marketing campaigns.
2- Offering online Software applications as services such as follow-up meters that assist individuals and organizations to measure their energy consumption and match up the resources accordingly for better resource organizations.
3-In-house projects installations: offering expertise and installation of roof-top solar panels and plantation).
column50: Our services and products will be a future turning points in developing countries as our non-renewable resources decline over time. Even-though the public within our region do not have extensive need to be more environmental aware. We have analyzed existing usage of energy saving products (such as energy saving lamps), and found that people tend to support a product if it will give them better budget planning over the long-term.

column29:
Main Competitors
Competitors: Synopsys, Cadence, Avery, PerfectVIPs, RockFish Technologies, IPExtreme, SmartDV, nSys Design Systems,Test and Verification Solutions, and others

Differentiation:
1)We work in niche market, Mobile memory market, our research shows that only one company provides verification solution for it, which is Avery.
2)Many of these companies donâ€™t want to risk the migration from old verification techniques to new ones, because of the effort and time needed in training the stuff, and because the experience with the old techniques will be reset. We apply new techniques in our products from the very beginning.

column33:
Problem: Digital electronic chips have become very complex, containing Billions of transistors on a space of nearly a few square millimeters only. It became nearly impossible to make sure that such chips are working well using old techniques. New techniques are needed to verify these chips(make sure it works as intended) in a faster and more efficient way.

We adapt the emerging technologies in the field to verify complex electronic chips. Our verification solutions will provide confidence that the final design of the chip is working as intended before being manufactured, saving the costs of remanufacturing (in case errors occurred in previous trials), which is about $100,000 per try, and decreasing time-to-market.

Our flagship product will be a solution that verifies Mobile memory chips, that exist in Smartphones such as IPhone5 & Samsung Galaxy SIII and tablets such as IPad3.
column40:
There are a lot of different digital electronic chips that needs verification solutions, such as Bluetooth chips, HDMI, WIFI, USB, Different kinds of Memory chips, Storage drives, Processors, and various interfaces.
Also, each of these chips has new specification standards every now and then, so as Bluetooth 2.0  is upgraded to Bluetooth 3.0 which needs another solution

The Vision is to create a complete library of verification solutions to every digital electronic chip possible

Product/Project Manager - Soud Hyder

Soud has a background in Computer Science and Economics and has vast experience in digital strategy and management. He currently is contracting for the Al Jazeera Network playing a leading role in the Africa digital media engagements as well as advising on new trends and workflow optimisation using digital media. He has also travelled extensively and thinks with a global mindset having lived in Malaysia, UK and currently Qatar. His postgraduate specialisation involved significant work in payment models and protocols. He also has commented and analysed use-cases of the M-PESA system in his native country Kenya.

Lead Developer - Mostafa Elaghil

Mostafa has a background in system development and has specialised in web applications and middleware. Educated in the UK, he worked as a System Developer for Kelvin Hughes, a Naval technology specialist. He has also consulted for various organisation in the UK, Japan and India. He recently moved to Egypt in order to fulfil his entrepreneurial ambitions and has a strong passion to utilise regional talent and skill to solve regional problems. He is tasked with developing a robust, scalable, secure and highly usable platform

Par ailleurs, EasyPay permettra de rassurer les acheteurs et les vendeurs Ã  distance. column27:
First we will start with Lebanon. We will speak with the UNRWA due to high gunfire in those areas and we will help the authorities there to catch the shooters. Then we will start our campaign in hot areas where gunfire is at its highest, mainly in Tripoli, then spread across Lebanon. We will attempt to spread in the middle east region in our first year.
We need a minimum of 3 active users in a radius of 1.5km during the day and 3km radius during the night for the application to work.
column29:
On a Global scale; our indirect competition is â€œShotSpotterâ€ (based U.S.A). We share the same goal but their course of action is not similar to ours on many fundamental levels.
ShotSpotter uses highly-developed sensors that are placed at variable- determined locations to detect shootings and sources of gunfire. This technology is sold at very high rates ($40,000 to $60,000 per square mile per year) , and is under the control of the client directly (the government). The problem is being solved but on a monopolistic level; the people and media donâ€™t have access to it because of its high cost.

On a Local scale : Our indirect competition is â€œMa2tou3aâ€, an application that reports traffic jams, shootings, protests and so on. The problem is that itâ€™s not as specific as us (providing us with a competitive advantage of differentiation and responsiveness) and it reports when itâ€™s publically known whatâ€™s going on (Meaning not within a short-time frame).
column30: Promoting global public safety and security by  helping to apprehend shooters, confiscate deadly weapons and deter gunfire activity that can terrorize the community.
column32: I will invest in developing and fine-tuning the application to improve the accuracy, by teaching the acoustic patterns of gunshots fired in a training field. Some of the money will go to a security company I will hire to make sure that the open source application is hack-proof and to verify that the application is respecting the  privacy of its users.
column33: The high cost of gunshot location and detection systems. By making this system we will promote global public safety and security against gunfire.
column40: Due to using the existing infrastructure from mobiles personal computers and laptops, and because it"s in the form of a web and mobile application, our system can spread all across the world.
column43:
We will sell the data to the government security agencies, press, premium users based on a subscription fee.
Users who can hear the shots will get the data for free.
Premium users are user who get data(location of shooter) but don"t use the application to send us data. Free users on the other hand will send us data(gps coordinates and time the shot was heard).
column50: I have studied our main competitors. ShotSpotter has been around for 16 years and still going. Ma2tou3a is growing by number of users, it started 4 month ago and already has 65000 users. Press has shown interest and we will have meetings with media outlets and security agencies.
column51: A mobile and web application crime-fighting tool that helps locate and track exact source location of gunfire using â€œacoustic triangulationâ€ then sends it to the security agencies in less than 30 seconds of gunfire.

-Today"s robots can do only repetitive tasks which it is programmed to do explicitly.
- Robots can deal only with a narrow set of objects and environment.
- Robots can learn, but in the same problem context, it cannot learn how to do a new task, which it does not know any prior
knowledge about how to perform it.
- Robots do not know any about its body, abilities, what it can do and what it cannot.
- Robots do not have enough intelligence to surf the internet?!
- Robots cannot operate in autonomous way and deal with unexpected situations.
- Robots do not have the intelligence nor knowledge to decide what it can do and what it can not ...

column33:
-Today"s robots can do only repetitive tasks which it is programmed to do explicitly.
- Robots can deal only with a narrow set of objects and environment.
- Robots can learn, but in the same problem context, it cannot learn how to do a new task, which it does not know any prior
knowledge about how to perform it.
- Robots do not know any about its body, abilities, what it can do and what it cannot.
- Robots do not have enough intelligence to surf the internet?!
- Robots cannot operate in autonomous way and deal with unexpected situations.
- Robots do not have the intelligence nor knowledge to decide what it can do and what it can not ...

column33: Achieving and maintaining healthy weight and lifestyle
column40:
The application can have a numerous amount of meal plans that can accommodate larger number of users tastes and food available for them or within their budgets.
Users can submit questions and receive consultation from our dietitian doctor.
the application can be integrated with Nike running app or any other steps counting platform to automatically calculate activity level and calories burnt and update their profile.
Progress charts and achievements section can be added and published to a success stories section.
Multilingual support.
Pop up meal tips and healthy food reminders can be pushed to users mobiles when they enter restaurants.
Healthiest users can be published for motivation.
column43: Through selling the application
column51:
an easy way (application) to help people achieve and maintain ideal weight and healthy lifestyle in a click of a button. The idea of this project came from the need to healthy individuals to have a guide that helps them find out the exact need of their bodies from calories each day, and not only that, because many available programs can do so. This program is going to suggest a meal plan that matches the amount of calories calculated for each person. 
The program will also tell the user if they are in the range of healthy weight, underweight, overweight or obese phase; according to that the program will either increase the amount of calories needed (if underweight) or decrease the amount of calories needed (if overweight) to facilitate further weight loss, and encourage reaching a healthier weight. All of the calculations in the program are based on scientific equations, and are approved by the World Health organization (WHO).
The program is going to ask the user to provide weight, height, gender, age and physical activity level. According to the numbers given, some calculations are going to be done, and the program will provide the user with the amount of calories that needs to be consumed per day, number of servings from each food group and will also suggest some meal plans.

Currently this startup is a one man show. My name is Charbel Keyrouz and I am trying my best to keep this startup alive and give it a chance to succeed.

I have 13 years of experience in software development, including development, architecting and management experience. I earned my B.S. in Computer Science from LAU (Lebanese American University) 

I think that my most valuable skills are my ability to quickly grasp and assimilate any new technology and the ability to tackle any problem and solve it. The latest problem that showcases these 2 abilities was to devise a DDoS defense mechanism for an online poker room and enabled it to fend off massive attacks of 3Gb/s. I also worked on improving the shuffler for that poker room.

Technically, what I bring to the game is a considerable architecting and development experience plus machine learning and AI experience. I love machine learning and AI and I am a firm believer that these disciplines will be a major force in the next evolution of the web.

These are estimates and per year. 

Office Rent + Lawyer Fees + Accountant Fees + Electricity + Internet = 25K

3 Senior Software Developers = 90K

We need at least 3 years of funding for this project to have a chance of survival. 
115K per year x 3 = 345K

During the first year we will find and implement the first solution for the first client. During the second year we should be able to get more clients and by the 3rd we should be able to generate income to support the operations of the startup. After the third we should reach a point where the generated income should attract more investors and will allow to grow the startup to a full fledged company.

Let give examples instead. These examples are extracted from a special report by The Economist on big data (Data, data everywhere - Feb 27, 2010)
* In 2004 WalMart peered into its mammoth databases and noticed  that  before  a  hurricane  struck, there was a run on Â‡fashlights and batteries,  as might be expected; but also on PopTarts, a sugary American breakfast snack.

* Best Buy, a retailer, found that 7% of its customers accounted for 43% of its sales, so it reorganised its stores to concentrate on those customersâ€™ needs.  

*Airline yield management improved because analytical techniques uncovered the best predictor that a passenger would actually catch a flÂ‡ight he had booked: that he had ordered a vegetarian meal.

It is these kinds of insights that we want to provide to banks and big retailers.
column40:
This is how we envision it. At first we will build custom made solutions then we plan to use the expertise collected to create a generic data solution available online that allows the SME to have the same power of insight as the big companies. 
Imagine for a second a big town retailer in Lebanon who just wants to understand how to increase his sales. He can simply connect his data our service and use it to provide him the insights we got from other retailers. In other words we have repackaged and sold him the intelligence of the big retailer. One such insight might be that he has a large demand for a certain product and we know from other retailers that that product goes very well with another product he does not have in his shop.

So we think we should be able to grow from simple software service provider to a region wide software as a service provider where our client will use our online service instead of our on site expertise.
column43: Banks and big retailers in the MENA area but we don"t have any statistic on the size of that market.
column50:
We are planning to experiment with 2 business models:
Make money out of the profit or savings we are generating for our clients. The service will be offered for free and we only want a portion of the saving or profit the client will be making. This approach gives a better chance to keep the ownership of the insights we will be finding.

Sell the solution as standalone software solution.
column51:
The first idea of this startup was to use Machine Learning and AI in order attack the information overload problem. The result was an app called the Morning Book (for more info go to http://www.themorningbook.com) but we were never able to get any traction with this first product so we thought that our best approach is to pivot and apply the things we learned to business data instead. 

Our aim for this new product is to combine artificial intelligence, statistics and art to transform reams of financial and economic data into gripping stories. In short we want the data to tell its story.

This product is not yet built but we have proof through the MorningBook app that we are able to transform a raging river of information that is Twitter into a docile stream. To achieve that goal we needed a way to make the computer â€œunderstandâ€ so that it can filter and sort. Understand that in some contexts "Apple" means the computer company not the fruit. Understand that in some contexts â€œsickâ€ might denote a positive sentiment. Neur0s was able to create an algorithm that allows computers to "understand". This algorithm is based on a mathematical way that allows computers to work with an intuitive, generalized idea of similarity.

Through our experience in the MorningBook we were able to amass a lot of know-how on converting data into meaningful stories and we want the chance to apply these techniques and technologies to data warehouses of banks and of retail stores.  

At first we will build custom made solutions then we will use this expertise to abstract away as much of the technical complexity as possible and create a product that will put the power of big data into the hands of any business user.

column19: Former Entertainment Journalist and Web Designer
column25:
Rana Fetit: Senior editor
An avid reader and writer. She believes that team-work is a paramount asset to get any task done, and has an attractive personality that combines unpretentiousness and seriousness at the same time, making her both an excellent manager for her organizing team and an editor constantly providing tips to her reporting team.

Omar El Deeb: Partnerships and fundraising
His experience as a former Student Union president provided him with skills in convincing others and negotiating agreements.

Kariem El Deberky: Partnerships and public relations
An enthusiastic management student whose presentable conversations and good negotiation skills have secured so far a good number of partnership agreements with student societies at AUC, helping us to widely grow their in only 3 months.

Shaheer Shaheen: Project head and editor-in-chief
With an experience of two years as entertainment journalist, and one and half years as the editor-in-chief of the first independent student media entity at GUC, his earned leading skills, connections with students and staff from different universities in Egypt and vision for this project are essential.
column27: Higher education students, faculty and staff in Egypt, then the Arab world.
column29:
El Watan newspaper has a section called "El Watan Universities" but it mainly deals with controversial (to them, news worthy) stuff. Our idea is not publishing news that would only appeal to the public, but rather mainly targets the students in a specific university, a much more bigger range of news reporting. e.g. at our GUC branch, we share condolences when a student dies.

- In AUC, there are 3 student publications currently active, Caravan, AUC Times and The Advocate. Caravan is a course at AUC, making their work much limited and in general lacks a lot of enthusiasm. The Times is a magazine, different set of content. Advocate is very poor in quality of design and content.

- In BUE, MIU, MSA and 6th of October there are no student newspapers. There have been quite few attempts to establish ones, but all have not continued.

- In state universities, there are a number of competitors, like Radio Mubasher in the engineering school of Cairo University.

Indirect competitors are the daily newspapers and mainstream media that provide coverage mainly when controversial things happen in universities (protests, violence,..)
column30:
-Interaction and exchange of ideas between students from different universities and majors.

- Providing a credible news source and preventing circulation of rumors

- Raising cultural knowledge and awareness

- Upholding essential community values: the hard worker and successful get to be portrayed in the media.

- Students learn to formulate opinions of their own to express themselves, as well as debate them sometimes.
column32:
- Start a recruitment campaign (we make interviews and written exams) to form teams in 6 more universities (beside GUC & AUC that we already have): MIU, BUE, MSA, CIC, FUE, UFE - (estimated total number of students is 60 thousand) by deploying booths in every campus and online advertising  and announce the launch of EgyInsider project (the umbrella under which all local teams are part of). ($2500)

- Make an opening ceremony in every university to officially mark the start of work, and for the team members to meet their team mates and be oriented on how we work. A "Welcome Pack" will be given to every member (containing INSIDER notepad, t-shirt with INSIDER logo, INSIDER mug,..). We would also invite prominent public figures from the press and media industries to give speeches. ($600 for each university x 6 universities = $3600).

- Release of the print edition of every university. Each university edition is primarily different from the other university"s, but contains some incorporated content as well.
(30 thousand copies of high quality 80gm white paper: $8,000 per issue. This secured seed-fund will help us quickly publish our early editions (2 or 3) until we make year-long agreements with sponsors. So it"s $24,000).

- Start workshops for our editorial team and organizing committee members. The editorial team would need training sessions by professional journalists, whereas OC members will need soft skills. All these things help raise the caliber of our team and their loyalty to the entity. ($200 per university x 6 = $1200 including with basic catering).

- Save the rest of the money in our bank account to the next year in the same process for more universities (mainly state universities like Cairo University, Ain Shams, Helwan & Azhar).
column33:
- Exchange of information, ideas and culture between students.

- Uniting and empowering students by interacting with the community to make a difference.

- Providing access for verified information regarding universities to the students of the Arab world as soon as they happen.
column40:
Currently we are at GUC (German University in Cairo) and AUC (American University in Cairo). We aim at establishing a local team at every university in Egypt by 2014, then the Arab world.

All these local teams are part of The Egyptian Insider project which would be the mother entity making quality assurance reports and making sure all local entities are up to the standards and abiding the rules.

This is one of our issues released at GUC: http://www.gucinsider.com/partnership/issue

- It"s important to highlight the role of our idea in being a media entity, that does journalism as well. We pay a lot of attention to our presence social media and the videos we produce and put on YouTube, giving our readers/audience the choice to follow our work in various formats.

The Insider (GUC):
http://www.gucinsider.com
http://www.facebook.com/gucinsider
http://www.twitter.com/gucinsider
http://www.youtube.com/gucinsider
column43:
Advertisement (in print and online), partnership and sponsorship programs, since the paper will be distributed on campus for free. However, sold for money in the street.

We have had ABB, the multinational electricity and energy company, as our sponsor to fund our work for the past year.

It"s worth mentioning that all team members (current and future) do not get payed for their work, as it is considered a student activity that they volunteer for to gain experience, as commonly practiced.

Also, the project success means being able to reach 2.4 million youth students in Egypt who are the driving force of almost every business and service on the market.
column50:
Generally, we made a study to gather important related facts, like the number of higher education students in Egypt being  estimated at 2.4 million, the number of universities and how many are state/privately owned, the events/occasions where students interact and meet.

In particular, at GUC and AUC we a survey to know how much is the students" interest in knowing about current events and what topics matter to them most. We perform this survey - with some enhancements - every academic year.
column51: Establishing the first and sole independent media company (newspaper + digital media) dedicated for and run by higher education students from Egypt and the Arab world.

Our idea is not publishing news that would only appeal to the public, but rather mainly targets the students in a specific university, a much more bigger range of news reporting. e.g. at our GUC branch, we share condolences when a student dies.

- In AUC, there are 3 student publications currently active, Caravan, AUC Times and The Advocate. Caravan is a course at AUC, making their work much limited and in general lacks a lot of enthusiasm. The Times is a magazine, different set of content. Advocate is very poor in quality of design and content.

- In BUE, MIU, MSA and 6th of October there are no student newspapers. There have been quite few attempts to establish ones, but all have not continued.

- In state universities, there are a number of competitors, like Radio Mubasher in the engineering school of Cairo University.

Indirect competitors are the daily newspapers and mainstream media that provide coverage mainly when controversial things happen in universities (protests, violence,..)
column30:
-Interaction and exchange of ideas between students from different universities and majors.

- Providing a credible news source and preventing circulation of rumors

- Raising cultural knowledge and awareness

- Upholding essential community values: the hard worker and successful get to be portrayed in the media.

- Students learn to formulate opinions of their own to express themselves, as well as debate them sometimes.
column32:
- Start a recruitment campaign (we make interviews and written exams) to form teams in 6 more universities (beside GUC & AUC that we already have): MIU, BUE, MSA, CIC, FUE, UFE - (estimated total number of students is 60 thousand) by deploying booths in every campus and online advertising  and announce the launch of EgyInsider project (the umbrella under which all local teams are part of). ($2500)

- Make an opening ceremony in every university to officially mark the start of work, and for the team members to meet their team mates and be oriented on how we work. A "Welcome Pack" will be given to every member (containing INSIDER notepad, t-shirt with INSIDER logo, INSIDER mug,..). We would also invite prominent public figures from the press and media industries to give speeches. ($600 for each university x 6 universities = $3600).

- Release of the print edition of every university. Each university edition is primarily different from the other university"s, but contains some incorporated content as well.
(30 thousand copies of high quality 80gm white paper: $8,000 per issue. This secured seed-fund will help us quickly publish our early editions (2 or 3) until we make year-long agreements with sponsors. So it"s $24,000).

- Start workshops for our editorial team and organizing committee members. The editorial team would need training sessions by professional journalists, whereas OC members will need soft skills. All these things help raise the caliber of our team and their loyalty to the entity. ($200 per university x 6 = $1200 including with basic catering).

- Save the rest of the money in our bank account to the next year in the same process for more universities (mainly state universities like Cairo University, Ain Shams, Helwan & Azhar).
column33:
- Exchange of information, ideas and culture between students.

- Uniting and empowering students by interacting with the community to make a difference.

- Providing access for verified information regarding universities to the students of the Arab world as soon as they happen.
column40:
Currently we are at GUC (German University in Cairo) and AUC (American University in Cairo). We aim at establishing a local team at every university in Egypt by 2014, then the Arab world.

All these local teams are part of The Egyptian Insider project which would be the mother entity making quality assurance reports and making sure all local entities are up to the standards and abiding the rules.

This is one of our issues released at GUC: http://www.gucinsider.com/partnership/issue

- It"s important to highlight the role of our idea in being a media entity, that does journalism as well. We pay a lot of attention to our presence social media and the videos we produce and put on YouTube, giving our readers/audience the choice to follow our work in various formats.

The Insider (GUC):
http://www.gucinsider.com
http://www.facebook.com/gucinsider
http://www.twitter.com/gucinsider
http://www.youtube.com/gucinsider
column43:
Advertisement (in print and online), partnership and sponsorship programs, since the paper will be distributed on campus for free. However, sold for money in the street.

We have had ABB, the multinational electricity and energy company, as our sponsor to fund our work for the past year.

It"s worth mentioning that all team members (current and future) do not get payed for their work, as it is considered a student activity that they volunteer for to gain experience, as commonly practiced.

Also, the project success means being able to reach 2.4 million youth students in Egypt who are the driving force of almost every business and service on the market.
column50:
Generally, we made a study to gather important related facts, like the number of higher education students in Egypt being  estimated at 2.4 million, the number of universities and how many are state/privately owned, the events/occasions where students interact and meet.

In particular, at GUC and AUC we a survey to know how much is the students" interest in knowing about current events and what topics matter to them most. We perform this survey - with some enhancements - every academic year.
column51: Establishing the first and sole independent media company (newspaper + digital media) dedicated for and run by higher education students from Egypt and the Arab world.

column30: The goal of this system is to provide technologies with the capability to generate clean energy at a cost that is competitive with fossil fuels.
column33:
In a limited resources country like Jordan, such a system could reduce the electricity bill in a significant way in summer.

Solar power is a relatively young sector and highly dependent on technology. Therefore, innovation is a key factor in enabling us to develop more efficient technologies with costs that are competitive to fossil fuel based energies when taking the cost of CO2 emissions into consideration.

column51:
My idea is about creating a contracting company specialized in solar systems to be used in parallel with HVAC systems.

The usual use of solar collectors is in space heating and domestic water heating. Recently, absorption chillers are being used for solar cooling which convert the collected heat from the sun to chilled water used for air conditioning. 

Air conditioning is the major electricity consumer in building sector. Using a Parallel system of solar cooling beside the usual AC could reduce the electricity consumption 70%.

column25:
Ikram Elkhadji, General Manager : majoring in Management information Systems with a job experience in different companies and positions like network administrator, software analyzer and designer, database administrator, and participated in several environmental projects as MIS (Management Information System) manager. Her past working experiences will empower her decisions and allow her to lead P.G to achieve its goals.  She will be able to communicate with each employee and convince them to give their best for the benefit of the company. As a general manager, Ikram Elkhadji will devise and plan company policies, and discuss them with the top management for final approval. He also has to devise and set up an annual budget and fiscal plan, and present it to the board of directors. Her working experience in the environmental sector will contribute to P.G success and help her to have clearer idea about P.G future plans.

 
Taheri Youness, Finance and Accounting Manager : is majoring in Management Finance with a job experience in different domains like banks, financial consulting firms and following financial situation of many small enterprises. As a finance and accounting manager, he will be in charge of showing the results of gains and losses, changes in value to reveal the progress or failures of Perennial Garden, and also its future limitations and opportunities. He has also to analyze and review the budgets, expenditures, revenues, expenses, payroll entries, invoices, and other accounting documents. Mr. Taheri Youness will help P.G to achieve its financial goals by keeping the management team aware about the finical situation of P.G and the feasibility of the projects that are taken.

column33:
Moroccan people are known to be familiar with gardens and green environment. The gardening field it is deeply related to Moroccan Culture, and this can be noticed by the availability of green spaces in Moroccan homes. However; people are still obliged to use conventional ways in creating and maintaining their green spaces. Thus, we provide our clients with a unique service and modern approach via our website to develop beautiful and functional gardens; to create something that lasts a lifetime, and brings an everlasting joy to our clients. Our focus is not only on the big spaces but also the smallest ones that can be converted to a balcony garden, where there are plenty of designs and ideas to choose from. In P.G, we work closely with our clients to produce imaginative and practical designs. We never seek to impose ideas. First we discuss our client preferences and needs of his green space, then we produce an individual design perfectly suited to his garden. 
The gardening industry in Morocco grows at a very slow pace and needs more investments to boost this industry. People still use the traditional ways in gardening and in the best case they hire unprofessional workers to do the job. Thus the quality is noticeably poor and people not complaining because the alternatives are very rare. Add to that, people in Morocco are not used to spend a lot of time in designing, due to the busy lifestyle. On our website we are providing solutions for these problems with reasonable prices.
column40: â€œOur vision is to be the leaders of the Gardening industry in Morocco and North Africa.â€
column43:
We are the pioneers in providing virtual garden experience in Morocco. We are going to provide the market 24x7 with new innovative ways to design gardens and balcony garden, in addition to free services and extreme quality work to let our customers enjoy the nature around their livings.

Also, our garden maintenance service is very active, quick and fun to keep the gardens in perfect condition all the year round.
so we will make money from designing gardens either in villas or balconies
column50:
Step: Meeting the client

1.	Meeting the Client 40 minutes Total 
2.	Expert will go to visit the place (Taking his Camera ,and portfolio,and copy of the fee  scale)
3.	Find the house before on multimap before he leaves  the office 
4.	Ask to see the garden
5.	Working Round the garden 10 minutes
6.	Let the client talk ,ask open questions encourage him  to open up
7.	Listen  to the client
8.	Once he has told the expert what he wants and what he think , expert will talk about Perennial Garden design philosophy
9.	Closing the deal  5  minutes
2nd Step:  Site survey &Write Report  

10.	Expert will collects site information such as existing paving, utility 
        boxes, existing trees & shrubs, downspouts, etc., and take digital pictures 
        of your site. 
11.	Expert will Come back office         
12.	Set survey to  understand the conditions in the garden
13.	Write report on his  visit detailing  the problem area and how he attends to solve  them(Include photos to illustrate his report )
14.	Include a quotation letter /contract as well as his T&C tense and conditions and invoice for his visit.



3rd Step:  Fisrt Meeting 

15.	Talk about garden needs ,materials â€¦ 
16.	Talk about 2nd step 
17.	Talk about cleintâ€™s budget + calculate the sq metrage of the garden and calculate the approx cost of the project 
18.	Explain cost per square meter principles and agree a budget from the financial manager 
4th Step: Concept Plans

19.	Guided by client design requests, a conceptual landscape plan will be prepared by IT manager and the expert showing proposed walkways, seating areas, focal points, with a preliminary planting layout.
20.	 Helps the client to see the garden from a wider perspective. Usually two or three different design options and layouts are presented to the client and a variety of ideas.
21.	Post it within 48 hours of our first meeting with the clients and the expert Follow up with aâ€ courtesy call â€œcall 5 days later if we havenâ€™t heard from them.
5th Step: sign Contract

22.	After we deal with the client and he choose the design and decide about thebudget of the essential works and then the extra budget for accessories.
23.	We sign a Contract with the client to start our work 
6th Step: Visual
.
24.	help the client to visualise the garden space according to the plan
25.	Show an exact and sophisticated image of the garden space, including all heights, levels, features, planting and furniture, etc.
7th Step: 2nd Meeting 

26.	Taking money from the financial manager for needed material 
27.	Contact the suppliers 
28.	Asking about any needed material or employees
29.	Deciding the deadline time of the project 
30.	And giving the signed contratc to the operational manager.
8th Step: Plan review and delivery 

31.	We will review the plan with the client for the last time 
32.	Start the project 
33.	Take picture of after project 
34.	Expert goes around with the cleint and see if he is satisfied with the result 
35.	take the project fees 
9th Step: 3rd Meeting  

36.	we will talk about the atfer project 
37.	expenses and profits
38.	and update the website putting the new pictures
39.	close the project file
column51:
Perennial Garden is offering online gardening service that will revolutionize the gardening system in Morocco from traditional systems to modern and innovative system. P.G is simplifying the designing process by providing an online tools in its website that help customers to design their gardens. Also P.G will provide out busy customers with predesigned packages like Traditional Moroccan Garden, Japanese Garden, Exotic Garden and Contemporary Garden. In addition to design services, Perennial Garden provides consulting and up keeping service which can be ordered via P.Gâ€™s website. P.Gâ€™s website and services will grant its customers high accessibility, instancy in response and long term relationship with customers.

      Perennial Garden will fascinate the Moroccan houses by its designs since the industry still growing in Morocco and has more demand for professional and creative ideas. Our business will have a huge success in the future because of the expanding market in Rabat region. Latest statistics show that there are more than 12015 villas in Rabat region, which is a huge market to operate in and there is more demand for housing all around the city. Adding to that, Morocco has now been more concerned about the green areas and nature and this will contribute to P.G success.

column33:
Moroccan people are known to be familiar with gardens and green environment. The gardening field it is deeply related to Moroccan Culture, and this can be noticed by the availability of green spaces in Moroccan homes. However; people are still obliged to use conventional ways in creating and maintaining their green spaces. Thus, we provide our clients with a unique service and modern approach via our website to develop beautiful and functional gardens; to create something that lasts a lifetime, and brings an everlasting joy to our clients. Our focus is not only on the big spaces but also the smallest ones that can be converted to a balcony garden, where there are plenty of designs and ideas to choose from. In P.G, we work closely with our clients to produce imaginative and practical designs. We never seek to impose ideas. First we discuss our client preferences and needs of his green space, then we produce an individual design perfectly suited to his garden. 
The gardening industry in Morocco grows at a very slow pace and needs more investments to boost this industry. People still use the traditional ways in gardening and in the best case they hire unprofessional workers to do the job. Thus the quality is noticeably poor and people not complaining because the alternatives are very rare. Add to that, people in Morocco are not used to spend a lot of time in designing, due to the busy lifestyle. On our website we are providing solutions for these problems with reasonable prices.

Dr Salam Elahmadi - Founder & CTO
Leads Menaraâ€™s Advanced Technology & Development team
-Hands-on entrepreneur and executive with strong project management and a cross-disciplinary background that includes signal processing, fiber optic communication, RF design, and mixed-signal IC design.
-Successfully launched industry-first telecom products enabling yearly multi-million dollar revenues 
-Over 16 years of experience in System Design, Test, and Deployment of wireless, wireline, and optical communications systems
-Author of numerous granted patents and peer-reviewed journals. 
-Invited speaker to technical events & conferences
-WDM Photonic Systems Architect, 2000-2002 - Qtera Corporation
- R&D Manager â€“ GSM/UMTS Wireless Systems, 1995-2000/2002-2003 â€“Nortel Networks
-Ph.D. EE.   

Siraj Elahmadi - Founder & CEO
received his B.S.E.E. and M.S.E.E degrees from the University of Oklahoma in 1989
and 1992 respectively. From 1992 to 1995 he was with Wiltel Communications, Tulsa, Oklahoma where he contributed to the deployment of some of the industryâ€™s early erbium-doped amplifiers. From 1995 to 1998 he was a Manager with Nortelâ€™s Broadband Systems Engineering. From 1998 to 2001 he was Vice-president of Product Line Management with Qtera, later acquired by Nortel. In 2004, he co-founded Menara Networks where he is currently the companyâ€™s chief-executive officer. Siraj, a frequently invited speaker, holds several patents and has co-authored several technical publications.  

Dr Matthias Bussman - VP of IC development
received the Dipl.-Ing. and Dr.-Ing. degrees in electrical engineering from Ruhr-UniversitÃ¤t Bochum, Germany in 1988 and 1992, respectively. From 1993 to 1995, he was Manager of ASIC/EDA at Micram, Bochum, Germany. From 1995 to 2002, he was Co-Founder, Chief Technical Officer/Senior Scientist at Multilink Technology, Santa Monica, CA. From 2002 to 2005, he was with Eltech Precision as President/CEO. Since 2005, he has been with Menara Networks, most recently in the position of VP of Engineering and IC Design. His interest is hands-on leadership in product development for high-performance analog/mixed-signal CMOS and BiCMOS based semiconductor and module products.

column33:
The goal of our project is the development of a noncoherent solution, implemented as a system-on-chip ASIC, for 100 Gigabit Ethernet (100G) fiber
optic communications. Internet traffic is expected to grow at a 34% CAGR between 2009 and 2014. Traffic growth is projected to exceed available network capacity in the near future, forcing network operators to deploy new solutions. The solution has to be low-cost, bandwidth-efficient, and compatible with existing optical networks infrastructure. This proposal makes it possible to develop a 100Gbps mixed-signal system-on-chip that will serve as key component within a cost-efficient noncoherent direct detection 100G fiber optic transceiver. The system-on-chip consists of fast data converters (ADCs &DACs), RF modulators/demodulators, tunable filters, variable-gain amplifiers, drivers, and a sophisticated signal-processing digital core. Its functions are 1) pre-process electrical signals prior to their transmission over the optical fiber, 2) process optically received signals to remove fiber distortions (such as chromatic & polarization-mode dispersion, nonlinear impairments) and recover the transmitted data. In contrast to competing coherent solutions which require a multitude of optical drivers, modulators, photodetectors, and coherent-optics components, the proposed solution uses novel techniques which only require a single modulator/driver and a single photodetector.
column40: According to Infonetics Research, optical transceiver market is expected to grow to $2.14 billion by 2014 with 40G/100G ports taking on a significant share. Moreover, per ATTâ€™s own prediction, â€œâ€¦every 10G lambda installed today will be a 100G lambdaâ€¦â€ (source: IDC June 2009). Forecasts such as these from industry pundits, system vendors and operators alike indicate that 100G deployment is both imminent and massive. Menaraâ€™s solution combines state-of-the-art DSP and RF techniques requiring fewer optical/electrical components as compared with competing coherent solutions. It thus allows for a compact 100G solution that is cost and power efficient (fewer components needed) and enables service providers to simplify their networks and reduce their cost-per-bit while increasing their port density.

column51:
Menara Networks develops innovative products and solutions that greatly simplify today"s layered optical transport networks. Leveraging the company"s proprietary high speed ICs, its extensive expertise in optical networking and system design, Menara products provide optical networks with superior performance and fewer network elements.

Menara"s value proposition translates to improved service velocity, and a significant reduction in overall network cost. Menara"s MSA-compliant optical transceivers with integrated ITU-T G.709 OTN enable our OEM customers to seamlessly and rapidly unlock the potential of their platforms by offering unique opportunities for expanded addressable markets and faster revenues.

Siraj Elahmadi - Founder & CEO
received his B.S.E.E. and M.S.E.E degrees from the University of Oklahoma in 1989
and 1992 respectively. From 1992 to 1995 he was with Wiltel Communications, Tulsa, Oklahoma where he contributed to the deployment of some of the industryâ€™s early erbium-doped amplifiers. From 1995 to 1998 he was a Manager with Nortelâ€™s Broadband Systems Engineering. From 1998 to 2001 he was Vice-president of Product Line Management with Qtera, later acquired by Nortel. In 2004, he co-founded Menara Networks where he is currently the companyâ€™s chief-executive officer. Siraj, a frequently invited speaker, holds several patents and has co-authored several technical publications.  

Dr Matthias Bussman - VP of IC development
received the Dipl.-Ing. and Dr.-Ing. degrees in electrical engineering from Ruhr-UniversitÃ¤t Bochum, Germany in 1988 and 1992, respectively. From 1993 to 1995, he was Manager of ASIC/EDA at Micram, Bochum, Germany. From 1995 to 2002, he was Co-Founder, Chief Technical Officer/Senior Scientist at Multilink Technology, Santa Monica, CA. From 2002 to 2005, he was with Eltech Precision as President/CEO. Since 2005, he has been with Menara Networks, most recently in the position of VP of Engineering and IC Design. His interest is hands-on leadership in product development for high-performance analog/mixed-signal CMOS and BiCMOS based semiconductor and module products.

column33:
The goal of our project is the development of a noncoherent solution, implemented as a system-on-chip ASIC, for 100 Gigabit Ethernet (100G) fiber
optic communications. Internet traffic is expected to grow at a 34% CAGR between 2009 and 2014. Traffic growth is projected to exceed available network capacity in the near future, forcing network operators to deploy new solutions. The solution has to be low-cost, bandwidth-efficient, and compatible with existing optical networks infrastructure. This proposal makes it possible to develop a 100Gbps mixed-signal system-on-chip that will serve as key component within a cost-efficient noncoherent direct detection 100G fiber optic transceiver. The system-on-chip consists of fast data converters (ADCs &DACs), RF modulators/demodulators, tunable filters, variable-gain amplifiers, drivers, and a sophisticated signal-processing digital core. Its functions are 1) pre-process electrical signals prior to their transmission over the optical fiber, 2) process optically received signals to remove fiber distortions (such as chromatic & polarization-mode dispersion, nonlinear impairments) and recover the transmitted data. In contrast to competing coherent solutions which require a multitude of optical drivers, modulators, photodetectors, and coherent-optics components, the proposed solution uses novel techniques which only require a single modulator/driver and a single photodetector.
column40: According to Infonetics Research, optical transceiver market is expected to grow to $2.14 billion by 2014 with 40G/100G ports taking on a significant share. Moreover, per ATTâ€™s own prediction, â€œâ€¦every 10G lambda installed today will be a 100G lambdaâ€¦â€ (source: IDC June 2009). Forecasts such as these from industry pundits, system vendors and operators alike indicate that 100G deployment is both imminent and massive. Menaraâ€™s solution combines state-of-the-art DSP and RF techniques requiring fewer optical/electrical components as compared with competing coherent solutions. It thus allows for a compact 100G solution that is cost and power efficient (fewer components needed) and enables service providers to simplify their networks and reduce their cost-per-bit while increasing their port density.

Selling the product to the interested persons in the  online advertisement service will be our  primary source of revenue , then  conventions with mobile operators and medicines suppliers to reduce the cost  of both the outgoing calls and the insulin used in the braclet will get more people interested in a cheap, less requiring health care tool.
Surveying the products will considerably allow a forward step in clients trusting the product and new clients willing to use it
column50:
Interviewing some health-care professionals indicated that most of their patients (diabetics) complained about the way their medicines are administered. being in a direct contact with the patients affirmed the point of the doctors,  the majority of the patients we asked were uncomfortable with both the indiscretion of injecting insulin into the blood and surveying the rate of sugar in the blood throughout the day.
Health-pocket is providing an efficient and practical solution to relieve the patients from their daily burden.
column51:
Using a bracelet conected to the patient"s phone via Bluetooth, the phone can measure blood pressure and pulse as well as the person"s heart rate and inform the user in case of anomaly. In case of a persistent anomaly the phone will take some emergency procedures such as sending a brief repport to the patient"s doctor or one of his family memebers indicating his location .
The bracelet will play the role of an insulin pump for diabetics and can be rechargeable at the end of each day, the dose and time of injection will be dictated by the patient on the phone.
The bracelet is discreet, attractive, convenient, and unlike the waste syringe.
The patient can forget that he is a diabetic during his day.

The Recruiting Assessment is an online web application that has a special skills tests and personality tests that will help companies/organizations/...etc to evaluate people skills and personality traits prior hiring or doing business with this person. The project will have 2 major parts:

1- first part for HR departments in enterprise companies for evaluating people Skills and personalities types that will help them in taking the hiring decision. the test restult will be compared with the skills required for this particular jobs opening

2- Second Part for Public Audience/schools: this part will help students identify their deep interests and personality types and suggest potential careers thus, help them decide about their purpose in life, what they like and what they hate, what would best match their preferences without the external effect of friends, media, and parents.
also, this will help public audience who is interested in knowing more about them selves.

column19: Environmental and Sustainability Consultancy in the Middle East and Gulf Regions
column25:
Eng. Ahmed Almazrouei is the Chairman of Ahmed Almazrouei group, he is the strategic mind of the business who gives a highly valuable insight to the project and its long term vision.

Eng. Mazen Al Jabi is the CEO of Ahmed Almazrouei Group, he acts as an adviser for the main decisions taken for the business operations. Eng. Mazen plays a major role during the development of the business plan and the yearly budget where his insight adds majorly to the project set targets.

Lubna Senan, is the Director of Green Consulting. She developed the vision of the project since early stages of the planning where she could identify major areas of operation, services and potential clients. Lubna takes care of the day to day operations including business development and marketing, recruitment and team management, follow up of technical operations as well as administrative issues.
column27:
In our business we work with various market sectors, our clients include governmental entities, private developers, industrial facilities, engineering consultancies, contractors, etc. out of our clients are the following:
Mimar Abu Dhabi Engineering Consultants, Architectural and Engineering Consultants, AMANA Contracting, etc.
column29: Our main competitors are international consultancies; however; our competitive advantage lies in being a locally owned company which understands local environmental conditions and challenges as well as appreciating the common practice of project management, our familiarity with different issues results from our team"s long experience in various industries in the region as well as being native Arabic speakers which makes it easier for us to reach out for decision makers.
column30:
The common vision of UAE government is to achieve the sustainable development target. Our group of professionals work extensively with different stakeholders to increase their awareness about importance of environmental issues as well as advise on the most feasible option of achieving sustainability targets.

In general the positive impact on the short run is supporting the sustainable development drive; however our main goal is the positive impact on the long run which will be reflected in better built up and natural environments for the future generations.
column32:
Our estimated budget for 2013 is as follows:
Salaries: US& 177,534
Personnel benefits: US$ 25,000
Marketing and business development: US$ 40,000
Operational Expenses: US$ 23,395
Office rent and administrative support: US$38,692
Contingency budget: US$ 17,205
column33: The creativity of our business lies in looking at various projects in an in-conventional way. Through a typical project we look at the owner objectives and goals, identify the most feasible environmental targets and finally working hand by hand with the design team as well as the project owner on embedding design measures that achieve all goals and targets.
column40: Once the business builds a solid ground in the consultancy part we are looking into going into the field of environmental technologies where we can provide comprehensive solutions to our clients.
column42: Our income for the year 2012 was estimated as US$ 274,055
column43: At the time being UAE, Oman, Qatar and Saudi Arabia with future plans to further expand to MENA region.
column50: The company has been so far self sufficient in terms of financial funding where our income of 2012  covered our direct costs.
column51: Green Consulting was initiated in March 2012, our core business is Sustainability and Environmental Consultancy. We play major roles in projects development where we advise different stakeholders of the most feasible options to achieve a sustainable development. We can provide services for different sectors including property development, industries, healthcare, tourism, oil and gas. Our involvement is throughout the project life from early stages of planning to project construction, completion and operation.
column52: Being a start up company in a mature market is the major challenge, due to the fact that sustainability and environmental consultancy is relatively a new concept in the region most stakeholders tend to select international companies originating from countries that have been implementing such standards for longer time.

column23: Smart Phone Application using GPS, IPS, and GIS Technology
column25: Mohammed Alkaff CEO
column33:
The big building such as big malls do not have interactive map to facilitate user shopping and save his time and sometimes he could search for a specific shop for a long time. The shops owners could not market their products and could not advertise the big sale easily inside big malls.
The proposed smart phone application will solve these problems by providing an interactive map and marketing and advertising shopsâ€™ products.
column51:
Smart phones are spread rapidly and many people depend on these smart phones on many ways. These smart phones are the future of computing devices and could replace many smart devices such as GPS devices, Cameras and PDA. In this work, I propose a smart phones application that using enhanced GPS and GIS technology. This application will be used inside buildings such as malls, hospitals, hotels and universities. We could use GPS enhancement for getting accurate location such as Indoor Positioning System. This application will define and describe these buildings from inside using GPS and GIS technology, and could advertise and market products of these buildings inside the application. These buildings do not have interactive maps that show a very detailed information inside the building. For example, the malls inside KSA only has a very simple maps located inside the maps and give simple information about the shops and does not direct the customer to the shop easily and he must suffer before he could find the shop especially in big malls. I propose a smart phones application that create an interactive map that provide the user with the exact location of the shops inside the malls and give detailed information about every shop such as shop name, shop number, shop opening and closing time, and shop activity, etc... In addition, this application can provide the user with the shop products prices and newest products and indicate if there is a sale on the shop.
The objective of this idea is to save the time of the users inside malls, find the shops easily, and provide them with a very useful information about mallâ€™s shops. In addition, the owner of the shops can market their products inside the application.

column51:
Near Brands will provide social interaction for two type of users
    -Brands outlets  owners like (cars outlets , closes shops , restaurants ,etc...)
    -The normal user
For Brands outlet Owners
-They will have their outlet places marked on the map
-They can post about their new offers , new items in stock  and sales
-Their posts will be shared to their followers and anyone caring about their brand category
For Normal Users
-They can subscribe their favourite brands, see their new offers and sales
-They can see their friends favourite brands
-They can see others rate opinion (comment) about brands and new offers on it
-They can post photos, videos,  and opinion tagged to the various brands

our cloud application can target the whole world especially that MOHR is a multilingual platform with English and Arabic version already developed.

our current plan is targeting the Arabic speaking market as a first phase.

the minimum number of registered companies in the Arabic speaking countries are 1.5million companies.

column51:
It is MO-HR and pronounced as MOHR.
MO-HR stands for MOVE-IT- Human Resource management system. In Arabic, MOHR means a little horse.
Building a new Multilanguage HR application may look a traditional investment with no satisfactory profit because of the high market competition. Okay, this may look right!. 
But the point is that MOHR will be the first Arabic cloud based HR system worldwide. Here is come the potential, it is all about using the new technology named cloud based applications.
The potential is in being cloud and the bigger potential is in being cloud in Arabic. So the add value of this business is being the 1st Cloud based Arabic HR app.
MOHR also adds value to community by allowing SMEâ€™s (small and medium enterprises) who were not able to manage their Human capitals through a good and reliable HR system to do that with MOHR and with a reasonable and affordable price and niche technology.
Below is our plan that shows the business opportunity. We will validate a payback period PBP of 29 months and an Internal Rate of Return IRR with 74% after 5years, and also positive net present value.
The product 1st version is ready to market, and was funded by MCIT (Egyptian ministry of communication and information technology) through a local competition. So the investment will be directed to marketing and continual enhancements of the product features and modules.

There is no permanent drop zone and skydiving school in Lebanon. 
The yearly average weather in Lebanon would make of it one of the best drop zones worldwide because it would be open most of the year.
In some countries like Dubai, they are forced to close during summer because of too much heat. In France the skydiving season is good between May and September because of bad weather during winter.

column27:
We believe that we have a born global product which will have no geographical barriers. As we mentioned above, we address the market of Aerial geophysical surveying services, NAICS 541360/ SIC 8713. Our first targeted customers are Petroleum & Gas companies for both pipe line as an asset management tool and geological investigation for oil falls, and other governmental bodies including (Ministries of Tourism, Agriculture, and Industry) will be interested in our technologies and services. As we are geographically located in Egypt, we will start by our local market then followed by regional market including North Africa, Gulf Council Countries and the rest of the African content. Then we will go to Europe and the rest of the world.
As mentioned above the GPR air vehicle has a variety of applications and use models in different sectors, solving different client needs with the same technology and application. Regarding only one segment, we have decided to illustrate the details of one of the target markets which, we believe, has high demand especially in Egypt and other African countries. This market is the landmine detection
column29:
The detector market is likely to be dominated by the metal detector in the short term as it is widely used, its strengths and limitations are well understood, and deminer Standard Operating Procedures and standards are adapted to its use. The market will become more fragmented by the introduction of new technology products, like ours, which meet the differing requirements and expectations of users in different countries.

So, speaking about competitors in EGYPT, there will be the metal detector providers who provide the government with it. those are our main competitors as we are presenting a new technology with a cost effective "switching cost".

Our indirect ones are the suppliers. As for our technology, we deal with a few numbers of suppliers.
column30:
Safety for deminers!

. We are able to provide our customers with the same final quality they target in a completely safe, fast and reliable solution. With our system, customers can survey/investigate areas they have never been able to reach, thus accomplish tasks that have been impossible to be accomplished before in a timeframe which is not comparable with the traditional alternative solutions. It"s a safe way that protects operators involved in demining activities.  Hitting a buried mine leads to serious injury or even loss of life. The value of investing in GPR technology can easily be realized by eliminating the human element. Putting aside the cost of demining and loss of service, what value can be compared against a human life?!
column32: It"ll be the first investment for our Market Product.
column33:
Regarding market, our product can address a couple of discovery, mapping and surveying segments, that each serve specific fields. We address Aerial geophysical surveying services, NAICS 541360/ SIC 8713. The mix of convenience, safety and accuracy does not exist inside this segment. Existing solutions involve human resources, thus exposing their lives to danger, or system to malfunction due to rough/ unleveled ground.
In order to show market pain, we will address the landmine detection segment. Contamination by landmines and all other types of unexploded ammunition usually called unexploded ordnance or UXO) is a worldwide problem with enormous humanitarian impact. At least 67 countries are being affected by land mines, but reliable estimates of the area affected worldwide are not readily available. Estimates of the number of mines laid vary widely, from 50 to 150 million. In the mid-1990s, humanitarian demining became a hot topic on the political agenda According to the 1997 Convention on the Prohibition of the Use, Stockpiling Production and Transfer or Anti-Personnel Mines and on Their Destruction (often referred to as the Ottawa Treaty), which entered into force in 1999, all stockpiles of mines should be destroyed within 4 years and all minefields lifted in 10 years.
In addition to antipersonnel mines, sub-munitions such as bomb-lets delivered by air or artillery, multipurpose weapons, and unexploded ordnance should be regarded as mines. These sub-munitions are often more difficult to identify and clear than mines.
"Every 5000 mines cleared one worker will be killed and two workers will be injured by accidental explosions." Nicolas E. Walsh and Wendy S. Walsh in the Bulletin of the World Health Organization 2003: Using the other common techniques will put 22000 deminer to death and 44000 will be injured besides the additional effects of the antipersonnel mines and the UXO (unexploded ordnance). Autonomous unmanned aerial system becomes a must, as robots become ineffective due to exposure to explosion.
In Egypt, all of our existing problems can be easily tracked to the wasted vast lands that nearly all are expected landmines areas! This was the real motive behind our product at the very beginning; to free Egypt of landmines.
â€œAll existing solutions expose my men to a certain degree of danger.â€ said General Taher Harby, head of engineers division in the Egyptian military, when we first told him about the vision to make our product. â€œIt would be very useful if we could have this ability to make such an accurate and safe detection process.â€ he concluded.
column40:
There are 120 million mines all over the world. Those create multiple markets as military or private contractors. The areas most affected by land mines include: Egypt (23 million, mostly in border regions); Angola (9-15 million); Iran (16 million); Afghanistan (about 10 million); Iraq (10 million); China (10 million); Cambodia (up to 10 million); Croatia (2 million); Somalia (up to 2 million in the North); Eritrea (1 million); and Sudan (1 million). The ability to enter advanced new products into the detector market will be significantly affected by the price elasticity of the market. Higher priced products at similar market volumes (inelastic market) are more likely if the potential benefits of using the new equipment are significant. A product which could improve the false alarm rate of current metal detectors by a factor of 10 could potentially double the overall clearance rate, resulting in savings of the order of $280k or more per square km. A proportion of such savings could be allocated to increased equipment costs during project budgeting.
The detector market is likely to be dominated by the metal detector in the short term as it is widely used, its strengths and limitations are well understood, and deminer Standard Operating Procedures and standards are adapted to its use. The market will become more fragmented by the introduction of new technology products, like ours, which meet the differing requirements and expectations of users in different countries.We can be The First Mover in alot of countries!.
column43:
We were able to develop our new GPR architecture and air vehicle in a fully integrated functional device with around 12% cost of the cheapest traditional GPR device found in the market. So our new architecture is not just accurate, efficient and effective, it is also economic.

The cost of Removing a mine without knowing its location is 1000$ While the cost while knowing its location is about 30$.!!

In Egypt, For example There are 4.8 billion barrels of oil that cant be accessed because of landmines! Also, there are 13.8 trillion cubic feet of natural gas!
column50: We"ve already marketed the project on Tv and Newspaper and the normal citizen can easily be familiar with our project as we were on alot of popular Tv shows in EGYPT.
column51:
A detection device that is highly sophisticated yet simple to operate. A system that is not held in hand, but is operated wirelessly. A seamless scan due to an air vehicle that you need not to worry about. A safe process with no earth or human contact. A map with all key objects (mines, cracks, rocksâ€¦etc.) is finally shown.

The product is based on an innovative radar technology â€”that is Ground penetrating Radar (GPR). It is a geophysical method that uses radar waves to image the subsurface. This method detects the reflected signals from subsurface structures.

Ground-penetrating radar antennas are generally in contact with the ground for the strongest signal strength. For use above the ground, GPR air launched antennas can be used. However, those systems were very large and heavy to the extent they were either fixed in location or installed on a van (bumper level). This rendered the whole process as difficult, very costly and thus impractical. Our product offers the end to the misery through a revolutionary invented architecture. We"ve designed the GPR module to be in no contact with the scanned surface unlike the typical GPR used now. The whole GPR technology is reinvented to over 

the land surface usage through mounting the GPR over an air vehicle providing safety and speed of scan.
